5300|"                                LIFE OF"|FALSE
5300|"                          JEAN DE LA FONTAINE"|FALSE
5300|"Jean de La Fontaine was born on the 8th of July, 1621, at"|FALSE
5300|"Chateau-Thierry, and his family held a respectable position there."|FALSE
5300|"His education was neglected, but he had received that genius which makes"|FALSE
5300|"amends for all.  While still young the tedium of society led him into"|FALSE
5300|"retirement, from which a taste for independence afterwards withdrew him."|FALSE
5300|"He had reached the age of twenty-two, when a few sounds from the lyre of"|FALSE
5300|"Malherbe, heard by accident, awoke in him the muse which slept."|FALSE
5300|"He soon became acquainted with the best models: Pheedrus, Virgil, Horace"|FALSE
5300|"and Terence amongst the Latins; Plutarch, Homer and Plato, amongst the"|FALSE
5300|"Greeks; Rabelais, Marot and d'Urfe, amongst the French; Tasso, Ariosto"|FALSE
5300|"and Boccaccio, amongst the Italians."|FALSE
5300|"He married, in compliance with the wishes of his family, a beautiful,"|FALSE
5300|"witty and chaste woman, who drove him to despair."|FALSE
5300|"He was sought after and cherished by all distinguished men of letters."|FALSE
5300|"But it was two Ladies who kept him from experiencing the pangs of"|FALSE
5300|"poverty."|FALSE
5300|"La Fontaine, if there remain anything of thee, and if it be permitted to"|FALSE
5300|"thee for a moment to soar above all time; see the names of La Sabliere"|FALSE
5300|"and of Hervard pass with thine to the ages to come!"|FALSE
5300|"The life of La Fontaine was, so to speak, only one of continual"|FALSE
5300|"distraction.  In the midst of society, he was absent from it.  Regarded"|FALSE
5300|"almost as an imbecile by the crowd, this clever author, this amiable man,"|FALSE
5300|"only permitted himself to be seen at intervals and by friends."|FALSE
5300|"He had few books and few friends."|FALSE
5300|"Amongst a large number of works that he has left, everyone knows his"|FALSE
5300|"fables and his tales, and the circumstances of his life are written in"|FALSE
5300|"a hundred places."|FALSE
5300|"He died on the 16th of March, 1695."|FALSE
5300|"Let us keep silence about his last moments, for fear of irritating those"|FALSE
5300|"who never forgive."|FALSE
5300|"His fellow-citizens honour him in his posterity to this day."|FALSE
5300|"Long after his death, foreigners went to visit the room which he had"|FALSE
5300|"occupied."|FALSE
5300|"Once a year, I shall go to visit his tomb."|FALSE
5300|"On that day, I shall tear up a fable of La Mothe, a tale of Vergier, or"|FALSE
5300|"several of the best pages of Grecourt."|FALSE
5300|"He was buried in the cemetery of Saint-Joseph, by the side of Moliere."|FALSE
5300|"That spot will always be held sacred by poets and people of taste."|FALSE
5300|"                          THE AUTHOR'S PREFACE"|FALSE
5300|"                   TO THE FIRST VOLUME OF THESE TALES"|FALSE
5300|"I had resolved not to consent to the printing of these Tales, until after"|FALSE
5300|"I had joined to them those of Boccaccio, which are those most to my"|FALSE
5300|"taste; but several persons have advised me to produce at once what I"|FALSE
5300|"have remaining of these trifles, in order to prevent from cooling the"|FALSE
5300|"curiosity to see them, which is still in its first ardour.  I gave way to"|FALSE
5300|"this advice without much difficulty, and I have thought well to profit by"|FALSE
5300|"the occasion.  Not only is that permitted me, but it would be vanity on"|FALSE
5300|"my part to despise such an advantage.  It has sufficed me to wish that no"|FALSE
5300|"one should be imposed upon in my favour, and to follow a road contrary to"|FALSE
5300|"that of certain persons, who only make friends in order to gain voices in"|FALSE
5300|"their favour by their means; creatures of the Cabal, very different from"|FALSE
5300|"that Spaniard who prided himself on being the son of his own works."|FALSE
5300|"Although I may still be as much in want of these artifices as any other"|FALSE
5300|"person, I cannot bring myself to resolve to employ them; however I shall"|FALSE
5300|"accommodate myself if possible to the taste of the times, instructed as I"|FALSE
5300|"am by my own experience, that there is nothing which is more necessary."|FALSE
5300|"Indeed one cannot say that all seasons are suitable for all classes of"|FALSE
5300|"books.  We have seen the Roundelays, the Metamorphoses, the Crambos,"|FALSE
5300|"reign one after another.  At present, these gallantries are out of date"|FALSE
5300|"and nobody cares about them: so certain is it that what pleases at one"|FALSE
5300|"time may not please at another!  It only belongs to works of truly solid"|FALSE
5300|"merit and sovereign beauty, to be well received by all minds and in all"|FALSE
5300|"ages, without possessing any other passport than the sole merit with"|FALSE
5300|"which they are filled.  As mine are so far distant from such a high"|FALSE
5300|"degree of perfection, prudence advises that I should keep them in my"|FALSE
5300|"cabinet unless I choose well my own time for producing them.  This is"|FALSE
5300|"what I have done, or what I have tried to do in this edition, in which"|FALSE
5300|"I have only added new Tales, because it seemed to me that people were"|FALSE
5300|"prepared to take pleasure in them.  There are some which I have extended,"|FALSE
5300|"and others which I have abridged, only for the sake of diversifying them"|FALSE
5300|"and making them less tedious.  But I am occupying myself over matters"|FALSE
5300|"about which perhaps people will take no notice, whilst I have reason to"|FALSE
5300|"apprehend much more important objections.  There are only two principal"|FALSE
5300|"ones which can be made against me; the one that this book is licentious;"|FALSE
5300|"the other that it does not sufficiently spare the fair sex.  With regard"|FALSE
5300|"to the first, I say boldly that the nature of what is understood as a"|FALSE
5300|"tale decided that it should be so, it being an indispensable law"|FALSE
5300|"according to Horace, or rather according to reason and common sense, that"|FALSE
5300|"one must conform one's self to the nature of the things about which one"|FALSE
5300|"writes.  Now, that I should be permitted to write about these as so many"|FALSE
5300|"others have done and with success I do not believe it can be doubted; and"|FALSE
5300|"people cannot condemn me for so doing, without also condemning Ariosto"|FALSE
5300|"before me and the Ancients before Ariosto.  It may be said that I should"|FALSE
5300|"have done better to have suppressed certain details, or at least to have"|FALSE
5300|"disguised them.  Nothing was more easy, but it would have weakened the"|FALSE
5300|"tale and taken away  some of its charm: So much circumspection is only"|FALSE
5300|"necessary in works which promise great discretion from the beginning,"|FALSE
5300|"either by their subject or by the manner in which they are treated.  I"|FALSE
5300|"confess that it is necessary to keep within certain limits, and that the"|FALSE
5300|"narrowest are the best; also it must be allowed me that to be too"|FALSE
5300|"scrupulous would spoil all.  He who would wish to reduce Boccaccio to the"|FALSE
5300|"same modesty as Virgil, would assuredly produce nothing worth having, and"|FALSE
5300|"would sin against the laws of propriety by setting himself the task to"|FALSE
5300|"observe them.  For in order that one may not make a mistake in matters"|FALSE
5300|"of verse and prose, extreme modesty and propriety are two very different"|FALSE
5300|"things.  Cicero makes the latter consist in saying what is appropriate"|FALSE
5300|"one should say, considering the place, the time, and the persons to whom"|FALSE
5300|"one is speaking.  This principle once admitted,  it is not a fault of"|FALSE
5300|"judgment to entertain the people of to-day with Tales which are a little"|FALSE
5300|"broad.  Neither do I sin in that against morality.  If there is anything"|FALSE
5300|"in our writings which is capable of making an impression on the mind, it"|FALSE
5300|"is by no means the gaiety of these Tales; it passes off lightly; I should"|FALSE
5300|"rather fear a tranquil melancholy, into which the most chaste and modest"|FALSE
5300|"novels are very capable of plunging us, and which  is a great preparation"|FALSE
5300|"for love.  As to the second objection, by which people reproach me that"|FALSE
5300|"this book does wrong to womankind, they would be right if I were"|FALSE
5300|"speaking seriously: but who does not see that this is all in jest,"|FALSE
5300|"and consequently cannot injure?  We must not be afraid on that account"|FALSE
5300|"that marriages in the future will be less frequent, and husbands more on"|FALSE
5300|"their guard.  It may still be objected that these Tales are unfounded or"|FALSE
5300|"that they have everywhere a foundation easy to destroy; in short that"|FALSE
5300|"they are absurdities and have not the least tinge of probability."|FALSE
5300|"I reply in a few words that I have my authorities: and besides it is"|FALSE
5300|"neither truth nor probability which makes the beauty and the charm of"|FALSE
5300|"these Tales: it is only the manner of telling them.  These are the"|FALSE
5300|"principal points on which I have thought it necessary to defend myself."|FALSE
5300|"I abandon the rest to the censors; the more so as it would be an infinite"|FALSE
5300|"undertaking to pretend to reply to all.  Criticism never stops short nor"|FALSE
5300|"ever wants for subjects on which to exercise itself: even if those I am"|FALSE
5300|"able to foresee were taken from it, it would soon have discovered others."|FALSE
