5300|"                                 JOCONDE"|FALSE
5300|"          IN Lombardy's fair land, in days of yore,"|FALSE
5300|"          Once dwelt a prince, of youthful charms, a store;"|FALSE
5300|"          Each FAIR, with anxious look, his favours sought,"|FALSE
5300|"          And ev'ry heart within his net was caught."|FALSE
5300|"          Quite proud of beauteous form and smart address,"|FALSE
5300|"          In which the world was led to acquiesce,"|FALSE
5300|"          He cried one day, while ALL attention paid,"|FALSE
5300|"          I'll bet a million, Nature never made"|FALSE
5300|"          Beneath the sun, another man like me,"|FALSE
5300|"          Whose symmetry with mine can well agree."|FALSE
5300|"          If such exist, and here will come, I swear"|FALSE
5300|"          I'll show him ev'ry lib'ral princely care."|FALSE
5300|"          A noble Roman, who the challenge heard,"|FALSE
5300|"          This answer gave the king his soul preferr'd"|FALSE
5300|"          --Great prince, if you would see a handsome man,"|FALSE
5300|"          To have my brother here should be your plan;"|FALSE
5300|"          A frame more perfect Nature never gave;"|FALSE
5300|"          But this to prove, your courtly dames I crave;"|FALSE
5300|"          May judge the fact, when I'm convinc'd they'll find:"|FALSE
5300|"          Like you, the youth will please all womankind;"|FALSE
5300|"          And since so many sweets at once may cloy,"|FALSE
5300|"          'Twere well to have a partner in your joy."|FALSE
5300|"          THE king, surpris'd, expressed a wish to view"|FALSE
5300|"          This brother, form'd by lines so very true;"|FALSE
5300|"          We'll see, said he, if here his charms divine"|FALSE
5300|"          Attract the heart of ev'ry nymph, like mine;"|FALSE
5300|"          And should success attend our am'rous lord,"|FALSE
5300|"          To you, my friend, full credit we'll accord."|FALSE
5300|"          AWAY the Roman flew, Joconde to get,"|FALSE
5300|"          (So nam'd was he in whom these features met;)"|FALSE
5300|"          'Midst woods and lawns, retir'd from city strife,"|FALSE
5300|"          And lately wedded to a beauteous wife;"|FALSE
5300|"          If bless'd, I know not; but with such a fair,"|FALSE
5300|"          On him must rest the folly to despair."|FALSE
5300|"          THE Roman courtier came, his business told"|FALSE
5300|"          The brilliant offers from the monarch bold;"|FALSE
5300|"          His mission had success, but still the youth"|FALSE
5300|"          Distraction felt, which 'gan to shake his truth;"|FALSE
5300|"          A pow'rful monarch's favour there he view'd;"|FALSE
5300|"          A partner here, with melting tears bedew'd;"|FALSE
5300|"          And while he wavered on the painful choice,"|FALSE
5300|"          She thus address'd her spouse with plaintive voice:"|FALSE
5300|"          CAN you, Joconde, so truly cruel prove,"|FALSE
5300|"          To quit my fervent love in courts to move?"|FALSE
5300|"          The promises of kings are airy dreams,"|FALSE
5300|"          And scarcely last beyond the day's extremes"|FALSE
5300|"          By watchful, anxious care alone retain'd,"|FALSE
5300|"          And lost, through mere caprice, as soon as gain'd."|FALSE
5300|"          If weary of my charms, alas! you feel,"|FALSE
5300|"          Still think, my love, what joys these woods conceal;"|FALSE
5300|"          Here dwell around tranquillity and ease;"|FALSE
5300|"          The streams' soft murmurs, and the balmy breeze,"|FALSE
5300|"          Invite to sleep; these vales where breathe the doves,"|FALSE
5300|"          All, all, my dear Joconde, renew our loves;"|FALSE
5300|"          You laugh!--Ah! cruel, go, expose thy charms,"|FALSE
5300|"          Grim death will quickly spare me these alarms!"|FALSE
5300|"          JOCONDE'S reply our records ne'er relate,"|FALSE
5300|"          Nor what he did, nor how he left his mate;"|FALSE
5300|"          And since contemp'raries decline the task;"|FALSE
5300|"          'Twere folly, such details of me to ask."|FALSE
5300|"          We're told, howe'er, when ready to depart,"|FALSE
5300|"          With flowing tears she press'd him to her heart;"|FALSE
5300|"          And on his arm a brilliant bracelet plac'd,"|FALSE
5300|"          With hair around her picture nicely trac'd;"|FALSE
5300|"          This guard in full remembrance of my love,"|FALSE
5300|"          She cried;--then clasped her hands to pow'rs above."|FALSE
5300|"          TO see such dire distress, and poignant grief,"|FALSE
5300|"          Might lead to think, soon death would bring relief;"|FALSE
5300|"          But I, who know full well the female mind,"|FALSE
5300|"          At best oft doubt affliction of the kind."|FALSE
5300|"          JOCONDE set out at length; but that same morn;"|FALSE
5300|"          As on he mov'd, his soul with anguish torn,"|FALSE
5300|"          He found the picture he had quite forgot,"|FALSE
5300|"          Then turn'd his steed, and back began to trot."|FALSE
5300|"          While musing what excuse to make his mate,"|FALSE
5300|"          At home he soon arriv'd, and op'd the gate;"|FALSE
5300|"          Alighted unobserv'd, ran up the stairs;"|FALSE
5300|"          And ent'ring to the lady unawares,"|FALSE
5300|"          He found this darling rib, so full of charms;"|FALSE
5300|"          Intwin'd within a valet's brawny arms!"|FALSE
5300|"          'MIDST first emotions of the husband's ire;"|FALSE
5300|"          To stab them while asleep he felt desire;"|FALSE
5300|"          Howe'er, he nothing did; the courteous wight;"|FALSE
5300|"          In this dilemma, clearly acted right;"|FALSE
5300|"          The less of such misfortunes said is best;"|FALSE
5300|"          'Twere well the soul of feeling to divest;"|FALSE
5300|"          Their lives, through pity, or prudential care;"|FALSE
5300|"          With much reluctance, he was led to spare;"|FALSE
5300|"          Asleep he left the pair, for if awake,"|FALSE
5300|"          In honour, he a diff'rent step would take.--"|FALSE
5300|"          Had any smart gallant supplied my place,"|FALSE
5300|"          Said he, I might put up with this disgrace;"|FALSE
5300|"          But naught consoles the thought of such a beast;"|FALSE
5300|"          Dan Cupid wantons, or is blind at least;"|FALSE
5300|"          A bet, or some such whim, induc'd the god,"|FALSE
5300|"          To give his sanction to amours so odd."|FALSE
5300|"          THIS perfidy Joconde so much dismay'd;"|FALSE
5300|"          His spirits droop'd, his lilies 'gan to fade;"|FALSE
5300|"          No more he look'd the charmer he had been;"|FALSE
5300|"          And when the court's gay dames his face had seen;"|FALSE
5300|"          They cried, Is this the beauty, we were told,"|FALSE
5300|"          Would captivate each heart, or young or old?"|FALSE
5300|"          Why, he's the jaundice; ev'ry view displays"|FALSE
5300|"          The mien of one,--just fasted forty days!"|FALSE
5300|"          WITH secret pleasure, this, Astolphus learn'd;"|FALSE
5300|"          The Roman, for his brother, risks discern'd,"|FALSE
5300|"          Whose secret griefs were carefully conceal'd,"|FALSE
5300|"          (And these Joconde could never wish reveal'd;)"|FALSE
5300|"          Yet, spite of gloomy looks and hollow eyes,"|FALSE
5300|"          His graceful features pierc'd the wan disguise,"|FALSE
5300|"          Which fail'd to please, alone through want of life,"|FALSE
5300|"          Destroy'd by thinking on a guilty wife."|FALSE
5300|"          THE god of love, in pity to our swain,"|FALSE
5300|"          At last revok'd BLACK CARE'S corroding reign;"|FALSE
5300|"          For, doubtless, in his views he oft was cross'd,"|FALSE
5300|"          While such a lover to the world was lost."|FALSE
5300|"          THE hero of our tale, at length, we find"|FALSE
5300|"          Was well rewarded: LOVE again proved kind;"|FALSE
5300|"          For, musing as he walk'd alone one day,"|FALSE
5300|"          And pass'd a gall'ry, (held a secret way,)"|FALSE
5300|"          A voice in plaintive accents caught his ear,"|FALSE
5300|"          And from the neighb'ring closet came, 'twas clear:"|FALSE
5300|"          My dear Curtade, my only hope below,"|FALSE
5300|"          In vain I love;--you colder, colder grow;"|FALSE
5300|"          While round no fair can boast so fine a face,"|FALSE
5300|"          And numbers wish they might supply thy place,"|FALSE
5300|"          Whilst thou with some gay page prefer'st a bet,"|FALSE
5300|"          Or game of dice with some low, vulgar set,"|FALSE
5300|"          To meeting me alone; and when just now"|FALSE
5300|"          To thee I sent, with rage thou knit'st thy brow,"|FALSE
5300|"          And Dorimene, with ev'ry curse abus'd"|FALSE
5300|"          Then played again, since better that amus'd,"|FALSE
5300|"          And left me here, as if not worth a thought,"|FALSE
5300|"          Or thou didst scorn what I so fondly sought."|FALSE
5300|"          ASTONISHMENT, at once, our Roman seiz'd;"|FALSE
5300|"          But who's the fair that thus her bosom eas'd?"|FALSE
5300|"          Or, who's the gay Adonis, form'd to bless?"|FALSE
5300|"          You'd try a day, and not the secret guess,"|FALSE
5300|"          The queen's the belle:--and, doubtless you will stare,"|FALSE
5300|"          The king's own dwarf the idol of her care!"|FALSE
5300|"          THE Roman saw a crevice in the wood,"|FALSE
5300|"          Through which he took a peep from where he stood;"|FALSE
5300|"          To Dorimene our lovers left the key,"|FALSE
5300|"          Which she had dropt when lately forc'd to flee,"|FALSE
5300|"          And this Joconde pick'd up, a lucky hit,"|FALSE
5300|"          Since he could use it when he best thought fit."|FALSE
5300|"          It seems, said he, I'm not alone in name,"|FALSE
5300|"          And since a prince so handsome is the same,"|FALSE
5300|"          Although a valet has supplied my place,"|FALSE
5300|"          Yet see, the queen prefers a dwarf's embrace."|FALSE
5300|"          THIS thought consol'd so well,--his youthful rays"|FALSE
5300|"          Returned, and e'en excelled his former days;"|FALSE
5300|"          And those who lately ridicul'd his charms,"|FALSE
5300|"          Now anxious seem'd to revel in his arms"|FALSE
5300|"          'Twas who could have him,--even prudes grew kind;--"|FALSE
5300|"          By many belles Astolphus was resign'd;"|FALSE
5300|"          Though still the king retain'd enough, 'twas seen;--"|FALSE
5300|"          But now let us resume the dwarf and queen."|FALSE
5300|"          OUR Roman, having satisfied his eyes,"|FALSE
5300|"          At length withdrew, confounded by surprise."|FALSE
5300|"          Who follows courts, must oft with care conceal,"|FALSE
5300|"          And scarcely know what sight and ears reveal."|FALSE
5300|"          YET, by Joconde the king was lov'd so well,"|FALSE
5300|"          What now he'd seen he greatly wish'd to tell;"|FALSE
5300|"          But, since to princes full respect is due,"|FALSE
5300|"          And what concerns them, howsoever true,"|FALSE
5300|"          If thought displeasing, should not be dispos'd"|FALSE
5300|"          In terms direct, but obviously dispos'd,"|FALSE
5300|"          To catch the mind, Joconde at ease detail'd,"|FALSE
5300|"          From days of yore to those he now bewail'd,"|FALSE
5300|"          The names of emp'rors and of kings, whose brows,"|FALSE
5300|"          By wily wives, were crown'd with leafless boughs!"|FALSE
5300|"          And who, without repining, view'd their lot,"|FALSE
5300|"          Nor bad made worse, but thought things best forgot."|FALSE
5300|"          E'en I, who now your majesty address,"|FALSE
5300|"          Continued he, am sorry to confess,"|FALSE
5300|"          The very day I left my native earth,"|FALSE
5300|"          To wait upon a prince of royal birth,"|FALSE
5300|"          Was forced t'acknowledge cuckoldom among"|FALSE
5300|"          The gods who rule the matrimonial throng,"|FALSE
5300|"          And sacrifice thereto with aching heart"|FALSE
5300|"          Cornuted heads dire torments oft impart:"|FALSE
5300|"          THE tale he then detail'd, that rais'd his spleen;"|FALSE
5300|"          And what within the closet he had seen;"|FALSE
5300|"          The king replied, I will not be so rude,"|FALSE
5300|"          To question what so clearly you have view'd;"|FALSE
5300|"          Yet, since 'twere better full belief to gain,"|FALSE
5300|"          A glimpse of such a fact I should obtain,"|FALSE
5300|"          Pray bring me thither; instantly our wight;"|FALSE
5300|"          Astolphus led, where both his ears and sight"|FALSE
5300|"          Full proof receiv'd, which struck the prince with awe;"|FALSE
5300|"          Who stood amaz'd at what he heard and saw."|FALSE
