5300|"          I find it, friends, not easy to decide."|FALSE
5300|"          THE case hangs up, and there will long remain;"|FALSE
5300|"          'Tis often thus when justice we'd obtain:"|FALSE
5300|"                    THE OLD MAN'S CALENDAR"|FALSE
5300|"          OFT have I seen in wedlock with surprise,"|FALSE
5300|"          That most forgot from which true bliss would rise"|FALSE
5300|"          When marriage for a daughter is designed,"|FALSE
5300|"          The parents solely riches seem to mind;"|FALSE
5300|"          All other boons are left to heav'n above,"|FALSE
5300|"          And sweet SIXTEEN must SIXTY learn to love!"|FALSE
5300|"          Yet still in other things they nicer seem,"|FALSE
5300|"          Their chariot-horses and their oxen-team"|FALSE
5300|"          Are truly matched;--in height exact are these,"|FALSE
5300|"          While those each shade alike must have to please;"|FALSE
5300|"          Without the choice 'twere wonderful to find,"|FALSE
5300|"          Or coach or wagon travel to their mind."|FALSE
5300|"          The marriage journey full of cares appears,"|FALSE
5300|"          When couples match in neither souls nor years!"|FALSE
5300|"          An instance of the kind I'll now detail:"|FALSE
5300|"          The feeling bosom will such lots bewail!"|FALSE
5300|"          QUINZICA, (Richard), as the story goes,"|FALSE
5300|"          Indulged his wife at balls, and feasts, and shows,"|FALSE
5300|"          Expecting other duties she'd forget,"|FALSE
5300|"          In which howe'er he disappointment met."|FALSE
5300|"          A judge in Pisa, Richard was, it seems,"|FALSE
5300|"          In law most learned: wily in his schemes;"|FALSE
5300|"          But silver beard and locks too clearly told,"|FALSE
5300|"          He ought to have a wife of diff'rent mould;"|FALSE
5300|"          Though he had taken one of noble birth,"|FALSE
5300|"          Quite young, most beautiful, and formed for mirth,"|FALSE
5300|"          Bartholomea Galandi her name;"|FALSE
5300|"          The lady's parents were of rank and fame;"|FALSE
5300|"          Our JUDGE herein had little wisdom shown,"|FALSE
5300|"          And sneering friends around were often known"|FALSE
5300|"          To say, his children ne'er could fathers lack:"|FALSE
5300|"          At giving counsel some have got a knack,"|FALSE
5300|"          Who, were they but at home to turn their eyes,"|FALSE
5300|"          Might find, perhaps, they're not so over-wise."|FALSE
5300|"          QUINZICA, then perceiving that his pow'rs"|FALSE
5300|"          Fell short of what a bird like his devours,"|FALSE
5300|"          T'excuse himself and satisfy his dear,"|FALSE
5300|"          Pretended that, no day within the year,"|FALSE
5300|"          To Hymen, as a saint, was e'er assigned,"|FALSE
5300|"          In calendar, or book of any kind,"|FALSE
5300|"          When full ATTENTION to the god was paid:--"|FALSE
5300|"          To aged sires a nice convenient aid;"|FALSE
5300|"          But this the sex by no means fancy right;"|FALSE
5300|"          Few days to PLEASURE could his heart invite"|FALSE
5300|"          At times, the week entire he'd have a fast;"|FALSE
5300|"          At others, say the day 'mong saints was classed,"|FALSE
5300|"          Though no one ever heard its holy name;--"|FALSE
5300|"          FAST ev'ry Friday--Saturday the same,"|FALSE
5300|"          Since Sunday followed, consecrated day;"|FALSE
5300|"          Then Monday came:--still he'd abstain from play;"|FALSE
5300|"          Each morning find excuse, but solemn feasts"|FALSE
5300|"          Were days most sacred held by all the priests;"|FALSE
5300|"          On abstinence, then, Richard lectures read,"|FALSE
5300|"          And long before the time, was always led"|FALSE
5300|"          By sense of right, from dainties to refrain:"|FALSE
5300|"          A period afterward would also gain;"|FALSE
5300|"          The like observed before and after Lent;"|FALSE
5300|"          And ev'ry feast had got the same extent;"|FALSE
5300|"          These times were gracious for our aged man;"|FALSE
5300|"          And never pass them was his constant plan."|FALSE
5300|"          OF patron saints he always had a list;"|FALSE
5300|"          Th' evangelists, apostles, none he miss'd;"|FALSE
5300|"          And that his scruples might have constant food;"|FALSE
5300|"          Some days malign, he said, were understood;"|FALSE
5300|"          Then foggy weather;--dog-days' fervent heat:"|FALSE
5300|"          To seek excuses he was most complete,"|FALSE
5300|"          And ne'er asham'd but manag'd things so well,"|FALSE
5300|"          Four times a year, by special grace, they tell,"|FALSE
5300|"          Our sage regal'd his youthful blooming wife,"|FALSE
5300|"          A little with the sweets of marriage life."|FALSE
5300|"          WITH this exception he was truly kind,"|FALSE
5300|"          Fine dresses, jewels, all to please her mind;"|FALSE
5300|"          But these are bawbles which alone controul"|FALSE
5300|"          Those belles, like dolls, mere bodies void of soul."|FALSE
5300|"          Bartholomea was of diff'rent clay;"|FALSE
5300|"          Her only pleasure (as our hist'ries say),"|FALSE
5300|"          To go in summer to the neighb'ring coast,"|FALSE
5300|"          Where her good spouse a charming house could boast,"|FALSE
5300|"          In which they took their lodging once a week;"|FALSE
5300|"          At times they pleasure on the waves would seek,"|FALSE
5300|"          As fishing with the lady would agree,"|FALSE
5300|"          And she was wond'rous partial to the sea,"|FALSE
5300|"          Though far to sail they always would refuse."|FALSE
5300|"          One day it happened better to amuse,"|FALSE
5300|"          Our couple diff'rent fishing vessels took,"|FALSE
5300|"          And skimm'd the wave to try who most could hook,"|FALSE
5300|"          Of fish and pleasure; and they laid a bet,"|FALSE
5300|"          The greatest number which of them should get."|FALSE
5300|"          On board they had a man or two at most."|FALSE
5300|"          And each the best adventure hop'd to boast."|FALSE
5300|"          A CERTAIN pirate soon observ'd the ship,"|FALSE
5300|"          In which this charming lady made the trip,"|FALSE
5300|"          And presently attack'd and seiz'd the same;"|FALSE
5300|"          But Richard's bark to shore in safety came;"|FALSE
5300|"          So near the land, or else he would not brave,"|FALSE
5300|"          To any great extent, the stormy wave,"|FALSE
5300|"          Or that the robber thought if both he took,"|FALSE
5300|"          He could not decently for favours look,"|FALSE
5300|"          And he preferr'd those joys the FAIR bestow,"|FALSE
5300|"          To all the riches which to mortals flow."|FALSE
5300|"          ALTHOUGH a pirate, he had always shown"|FALSE
5300|"          Much honour in his acts, as well was known;"|FALSE
5300|"          But Cupid's frolicks were his heart's delight:"|FALSE
5300|"          None truly brave can ever beauty slight;"|FALSE
5300|"          A sailor's always bold and kind and free,"|FALSE
5300|"          Good lib'ral fellows, such they'll ever be;"|FALSE
5300|"          'Mong saints indeed 'twere vain their names to seek!"|FALSE
5300|"          The man was good howe'er of whom we speak;"|FALSE
5300|"          His usual name was Pagamin Montegue;"|FALSE
5300|"          For hours the lady's screams were heard a league,"|FALSE
5300|"          While he each minute anxiously would seize,"|FALSE
5300|"          To cheer her spirits and her heart to please;"|FALSE
5300|"          T'attain his wish he ev'ry art combined;"|FALSE
5300|"          At length the lovely captive all resigned."|FALSE
5300|"          'Twas Cupid conquer'd, Cupid with his dart;"|FALSE
5300|"          A thousand times more pirate in his art,"|FALSE
5300|"          Than Pagamin; on bleeding hearts he preys,"|FALSE
5300|"          But little quarter gives, nor grace displays:"|FALSE
5300|"          To pay her ransom she'd enough of gold;"|FALSE
5300|"          For this her spouse was truly never cold;"|FALSE
5300|"          No fast nor festival therein appear'd,"|FALSE
5300|"          And her captivity he greatly fear'd."|FALSE
5300|"          THIS calendar o'erspread with rubrick days;"|FALSE
5300|"          She soon forgot and learn'd the pirate's ways;"|FALSE
5300|"          The matrimonial zone aside was thrown,"|FALSE
5300|"          And only mentioned where the fact was known:"|FALSE
5300|"          OUR lawyer would his fingers sooner burn;"|FALSE
5300|"          Than have his wife but virtuous home return;"|FALSE
5300|"          By means of gold he entertain'd no doubt,"|FALSE
5300|"          Her restoration might be brought about."|FALSE
5300|"          A passport from the pirate he obtain'd,"|FALSE
5300|"          Then waited on him and his wish explain'd;"|FALSE
5300|"          To pay he offer'd what soe'er he'd ask;"|FALSE
5300|"          His terms accept, though hard perhaps the task;"|FALSE
5300|"          THE robber answer'd, if my name around,"|FALSE
5300|"          Be not for honourable acts renown'd,"|FALSE
5300|"          'Tis quite unjust:--your partner I'll restore"|FALSE
5300|"          In health, without a ransom:--would you more?"|FALSE
5300|"          A friendship so respect'd, heav'n forefend!"|FALSE
5300|"          Should ever, by my conduct, have an end."|FALSE
5300|"          The fair, whom you so ardently admire,"|FALSE
5300|"          Shall to your arms return as you desire,"|FALSE
5300|"          Such pleasure to a friend I would not sell;"|FALSE
5300|"          Convince me that she's your's, and all is well;"|FALSE
5300|"          For if another I to you should give,"|FALSE
5300|"          (And many that I've taken with me live,)"|FALSE
5300|"          I surely should incur a heavy blame;"|FALSE
5300|"          I lately captur'd one, a charming dame,"|FALSE
5300|"          With auburn locks, a little fat, tall, young;"|FALSE
5300|"          If she declare she does to you belong,"|FALSE
5300|"          When you she's seen, I will the belle concede;"|FALSE
5300|"          You'll take her instantly; I'll not impede."|FALSE
5300|"          THE sage replied, your conduct's truly wise;"|FALSE
5300|"          Such wond'rous kindness fills me with surprise;"|FALSE
5300|"          But since 'tis said that every trade must live,"|FALSE
5300|"          The sum just mention:--I'll the ransom give;"|FALSE
5300|"          No compliment I wish, my purse behold"|FALSE
5300|"          You know the money presently is told;"|FALSE
5300|"          Consider me a stranger now I pray;"|FALSE
5300|"          With you I'd equal probity display,"|FALSE
5300|"          And so will act, I swear, as you shall see;"|FALSE
5300|"          There 's not a doubt the fair will go with me;"|FALSE
5300|"          My word for this I would not have you take:--"|FALSE
5300|"          You'll see how happy 'twill the lady make"|FALSE
5300|"          To find me here; to my embrace she'll fly;"|FALSE
5300|"          My only fears--that she of joy will die."|FALSE
5300|"          To them the charmer now was instant brought,"|FALSE
5300|"          Who eyed her husband as beneath a thought;"|FALSE
5300|"          Received him coldly, just as if he'd been"|FALSE
5300|"          A stranger from Peru, she ne'er had seen."|FALSE
5300|"          LOOK, said Quinzica, she's ashamed 'tis plain"|FALSE
5300|"          So many lookers on her love restrain;"|FALSE
5300|"          But be assured, if we were left alone,"|FALSE
5300|"          Around my neck her arms would soon be thrown."|FALSE
5300|"          IF this, replied the pirate, you believe,"|FALSE
5300|"          Attend her toilet:--naught can then deceive."|FALSE
5300|"          Away they went, and closely shut the door;"|FALSE
5300|"          When Richard said, thou darling of my store,"|FALSE
5300|"          How can'st thou thus behave? my pretty dove,"|FALSE
5300|"          'Tis thy Quinzica, come to seek his love,"|FALSE
5300|"          In all the same, except about his wife;"|FALSE
5300|"          Dost in this face a change observe my life?"|FALSE
5300|"          'Tis grieving for thy loss that makes me ill;"|FALSE
5300|"          Did ever I in aught deny thy will?"|FALSE
5300|"          In dress or play could any thee exceed?"|FALSE
5300|"          And had'st thou not whatever thou might'st need?"|FALSE
5300|"          To please thee, oft I made myself a slave;"|FALSE
5300|"          Such thou art now; but thee again I crave."|FALSE
5300|"          Then what dost think about thy honour, dear?--"|FALSE
5300|"          Said she, with ire, I neither know nor fear;"|FALSE
5300|"          Is this a time to guard it, do you say?"|FALSE
5300|"          What pain was shown by any one, I pray;"|FALSE
5300|"          When I was forc'd to wed a man like you,"|FALSE
5300|"          Old, impotent, and hateful to the view,"|FALSE
5300|"          While I was young and blooming as the morn,"|FALSE
5300|"          Deserving truly, something less forlorn,"|FALSE
5300|"          And seemingly intended to possess"|FALSE
5300|"          What Hymen best in store has got to bless;"|FALSE
5300|"          For I was thought by all the world around,"|FALSE
5300|"          Most worthy ev'ry bliss in wedlock found."|FALSE
5300|"          YET things took quite another turn with me"|FALSE
5300|"          In tune my husband never proved to be,"|FALSE
5300|"          Except a feast or two throughout the year;"|FALSE
5300|"          From Pagamin I met a diff'rent cheer;"|FALSE
5300|"          Another lesson presently he taught;"|FALSE
5300|"          The life's sweet pleasures more the pirate brought,"|FALSE
5300|"          In two short days, than e'er I had from you"|FALSE
5300|"          In those four years that only you I knew."|FALSE
5300|"          PRAY leave me husband:--let me have my will"|FALSE
5300|"          Insist not on my living with you still;"|FALSE
5300|"          No calendars with Pagamin are seen--"|FALSE
5300|"          Far better treated with the man I've been."|FALSE
5300|"          My other friends and you much worse deserved:"|FALSE
5300|"          The spouse, for taking me when quite unnerved,"|FALSE
5300|"          And they, for giving preference base to gold,"|FALSE
5300|"          To those pure joys--far better thought than told."|FALSE
5300|"          But Pagamin in ev'ry way can please;"|FALSE
5300|"          And though no code he owns, yet all is ease;"|FALSE
5300|"          Himself will tell you what has passed this morn,"|FALSE
5300|"          His actions would a sov'reign prince adorn."|FALSE
5300|"          Such information may excite surprise,"|FALSE
5300|"          But now the truth, 'twere useless to disguise,"|FALSE
5300|"          Nothing will gain belief, we've no one near"|FALSE
5300|"          To witness our discourse:--adieu, my dear,"|FALSE
5300|"          To all your festivals--I'm flesh and blood:--"|FALSE
5300|"          Gems, dresses, ornaments, do little good;"|FALSE
5300|"          You know full well, betwixt the head and heel,"|FALSE
5300|"          Though little's said, yet much we often feel."|FALSE
5300|"          On this she stopt, and Richard dropt his chin,"|FALSE
5300|"          Rejoiced to 'scape from such unwelcome din."|FALSE
5300|"          BARTHOLOMEA, pleased with what had passed;"|FALSE
5300|"          No disposition showed to hold him fast;"|FALSE
5300|"          The downcast husband felt such poignant grief,"|FALSE
5300|"          With ills where age can scarcely hope relief,"|FALSE
5300|"          That soon he left this busy stage of life,"|FALSE
5300|"          And Pagamin the widow took to wife."|FALSE
5300|"          The deed was just, for neither of the two"|FALSE
5300|"          E'er felt what oft in Richard rose to view;"|FALSE
5300|"          From feeling proof arose their mutual choice;"|FALSE
5300|"          And 'tween them ne'er was heard the jarring voice."|FALSE
5300|"          BEHOLD a lesson for the aged man;"|FALSE
5300|"          Who thinks, when old, to act as he began;"|FALSE
5300|"          But, if the sage a yielding dotard seems,"|FALSE
5300|"          His work is done by those the wife esteems;"|FALSE
5300|"          Complaints are never heard; no thrilling fears;"|FALSE
5300|"          And ev'ry one around at ease appears."|FALSE
5300|"                     THE AVARICIOUS WIFE AND"|FALSE
5300|"                        TRICKING GALLANT"|FALSE
5300|"          WHO knows the world will never feel surprise,"|FALSE
5300|"          When men are duped by artful women's eyes;"|FALSE
5300|"          Though death his weapon freely will unfold;"|FALSE
5300|"          Love's pranks, we find, are ever ruled by gold."|FALSE
5300|"          To vain coquettes I doubtless here allude;"|FALSE
5300|"          But spite of arts with which they're oft endued;"|FALSE
5300|"          I hope to show (our honour to maintain,)"|FALSE
5300|"          We can, among a hundred of the train,"|FALSE
5300|"          Catch one at least, and play some cunning trick:--"|FALSE
5300|"          For instance, take blithe Gulphar's wily nick,"|FALSE
5300|"          Who gained (old soldier-like) his ardent aim,"|FALSE
5300|"          And gratis got an avaricious dame."|FALSE
5300|"          LOOK well at this, ye heroes of the sword,"|FALSE
5300|"          Howe'er with wily freaks your heads be stored,"|FALSE
5300|"          Beyond a doubt, at court I now could find,"|FALSE
5300|"          A host of lovers of the Gulphar kind."|FALSE
5300|"          To Gasperin's so often went our wight,"|FALSE
5300|"          The wife at length became his sole delight,"|FALSE
5300|"          Whose youth and beauty were by all confessed;"|FALSE
5300|"          But, 'midst these charms, such av'rice she possessed,"|FALSE
5300|"          The warmest love was checked--a thing not rare,"|FALSE
5300|"          In modern times at least, among the FAIR."|FALSE
5300|"          'Tis true, as I've already said, with such"|FALSE
5300|"          Sighs naught avail, and promises not much;"|FALSE
5300|"          Without a purse, who wishes should express,"|FALSE
5300|"          Would vainly hope to gain a soft caress."|FALSE
5300|"          The god of love no other charm employs,"|FALSE
5300|"          Then cards, and dress, and pleasure's cheering joys;"|FALSE
5300|"          From whose gay shops more cuckolds we behold,"|FALSE
5300|"          Than heroes sallied from Troy's horse of old."|FALSE
5300|"          BUT to our lady's humour let's adhere;"|FALSE
5300|"          Sighs passed for naught: they entered not her ear;"|FALSE
5300|"          'Twas speaking only would the charmer please,"|FALSE
5300|"          The reader, without doubt, my meaning sees;"|FALSE
5300|"          Gay Gulphar plainly spoke, and named a sum"|FALSE
5300|"          A hundred pounds, she listened:--was o'ercome."|FALSE
5300|"          OUR wight the cash by Gasperin was lent;"|FALSE
5300|"          And then the husband to the country went,"|FALSE
5300|"          Without suspecting that his loving mate,"|FALSE
5300|"          Designed with horns to ornament his pate."|FALSE
5300|"          THE money artful Gulphar gave the dame,"|FALSE
5300|"          While friends were round who could observe the same;"|FALSE
5300|"          Here, said the spark, a hundred pounds receive,"|FALSE
5300|"          'Tis for your spouse:--the cash with you I leave."|FALSE
5300|"          The lady fancied what the swain had said,"|FALSE
5300|"          Was policy, and to concealment led."|FALSE
5300|"          NEXT morn our belle regaled the arch gallant,"|FALSE
5300|"          Fulfilled his promise:--and his eager want."|FALSE
5300|"          Day after day he followed up the game;"|FALSE
5300|"          For cash he took, and int'rest on the same;"|FALSE
5300|"          Good payers get, we always may conclude,"|FALSE
5300|"          Full measure served, whatever is pursued."|FALSE
5300|"          WHEN Gasperin returned, our crafty wight,"|FALSE
5300|"          Before the wife addressed her spouse at sight;"|FALSE
5300|"          Said he the cash I've to your lady paid,"|FALSE
5300|"          Not having (as I feared) required its aid;"|FALSE
5300|"          To save mistakes, pray cross it in your book;"|FALSE
5300|"          The lady, thunderstruck, with terror shook;"|FALSE
5300|"          Allowed the payment; 'twas a case too clear;"|FALSE
5300|"          In truth for character she 'gan to fear."|FALSE
5300|"          But most howe'er she grudged the surplus joy,"|FALSE
5300|"          Bestowed on such a vile, deceitful boy."|FALSE
5300|"          THE loss was doubtless great in ev'ry view"|FALSE
5300|"          Around the town the wicked Gulphar flew;"|FALSE
5300|"          In all the streets, at every house to tell,"|FALSE
5300|"          How nicely he had trick'd the greedy belle."|FALSE
5300|"          To blame him useless 'twere you must allow;"|FALSE
5300|"          The French such frolicks readily avow."|FALSE
5300|"                     THE JEALOUS HUSBAND"|FALSE
5300|"          A CERTAIN husband who, from jealous fear,"|FALSE
5300|"          With one eye slept while t'other watched his dear,"|FALSE
5300|"          Deprived his wife of every social joy,"|FALSE
5300|"          (Friends oft the jealous character annoy,)"|FALSE
5300|"          And made a fine collection in a book,"|FALSE
5300|"          Of tricks with which the sex their wishes hook."|FALSE
5300|"          Strange fool! as if their wiles, to speak the truth,"|FALSE
5300|"          Were not a hydra, both in age and youth."|FALSE
5300|"          HIS wife howe'er engaged his constant cares;"|FALSE
5300|"          He counted e'en the number of her hairs;"|FALSE
5300|"          And kept a hag who followed every hour,"|FALSE
5300|"          Where'er she went, each motion to devour;"|FALSE
5300|"          Duenna like, true semblance of a shade,"|FALSE
5300|"          That never quits, yet moves as if afraid."|FALSE
5300|"          THIS arch collection, like a prayer-book bound;"|FALSE
5300|"          Was in the blockhead's pocket always found,"|FALSE
5300|"          The form religious of the work, he thought,"|FALSE
5300|"          Would prove a charm 'gainst vice whenever sought!"|FALSE
5300|"          ONE holy day, it happened that our dame,"|FALSE
5300|"          As from the neighb'ring church she homeward came;"|FALSE
5300|"          And passed a house, some wight, concealed from view;"|FALSE
5300|"          A basket full of filth upon her threw."|FALSE
5300|"          WITH anxious care apologies were made;"|FALSE
5300|"          The lady, frightened by the frolick played,"|FALSE
5300|"          Quite unsuspicious to the mansion went;"|FALSE
5300|"          Her aged friend for other clothes she sent,"|FALSE
5300|"          Who hurried home, and ent'ring out of breath;"|FALSE
5300|"          Informed old hunks--what pained him more than death"|FALSE
5300|"          ZOUNDS! cried the latter, vainly I may look"|FALSE
5300|"          To find a case like this within my book;"|FALSE
5300|"          A dupe I'm made, and nothing can be worse:--"|FALSE
5300|"          Hell seize the work--'tis thoroughly a curse!"|FALSE
5300|"          NOT wrong he proved, for, truly to confess;"|FALSE
5300|"          This throwing dirt upon the lady's dress"|FALSE
5300|"          Was done to get the hag, with Argus' eyes"|FALSE
5300|"          Removed a certain distance from the prize."|FALSE
5300|"          The gay gallant, who watched the lucky hour,"|FALSE
5300|"          Felt doubly blessed to have her in his power."|FALSE
5300|"          HOW vain our schemes to guard the wily sex!"|FALSE
5300|"          Oft plots we find, that ev'ry sense perplex."|FALSE
5300|"          Go, jealous husbands, books of cases burn;"|FALSE
5300|"          Caresses lavish, and you'll find return."|FALSE
5300|"                       THE GASCON PUNISHED"|FALSE
5300|"          A GASCON (being heard one day to swear,"|FALSE
5300|"          That he'd possess'd a certain lovely fair,)"|FALSE
5300|"          Was played a wily trick, and nicely served;"|FALSE
5300|"          'Twas clear, from truth he shamefully had swerved:"|FALSE
5300|"          But those who scandal propagate below,"|FALSE
5300|"          Are prophets thought, and ev'ry action know;"|FALSE
5300|"          While good, if spoken, scarcely is believed,"|FALSE
5300|"          And must be viewed, or not for truth received."|FALSE
5300|"          THE dame, indeed, the Gascon only jeered,"|FALSE
5300|"          And e'er denied herself when he appeared;"|FALSE
5300|"          But when she met the wight, who sought to shine;"|FALSE
5300|"          And called her angel, beauteous and divine,"|FALSE
5300|"          She fled and hastened to a female friend,"|FALSE
5300|"          Where she could laugh, and at her ease unbend."|FALSE
5300|"          NEAR Phillis, (our fair fugitive) there dwelled"|FALSE
5300|"          One Eurilas, his nearest neighbour held;"|FALSE
5300|"          His wife was Cloris; 'twas with her our dove"|FALSE
5300|"          Took shelter from the Gascon's forward love,"|FALSE
5300|"          Whose name was Dorilas; and Damon young,"|FALSE
5300|"          (The Gascon's friend) on whom gay Cloris hung."|FALSE
5300|"          SWEET Phillis, by her manner, you might see,"|FALSE
5300|"          From sly amours and dark intrigues was free;"|FALSE
5300|"          The value to possess her no one knew,"|FALSE
5300|"          Though all admired the lovely belle at view."|FALSE
5300|"          Just twenty years she counted at the time,"|FALSE
5300|"          And now a widow was, though in her prime,"|FALSE
5300|"          (Her spouse, an aged dotard, worth a plum:--"|FALSE
5300|"          Of those whose loss to mourn no tears e'er come.)"|FALSE
5300|"          OUR seraph fair, such loveliness possessed,"|FALSE
5300|"          In num'rous ways a Gascon could have blessed;"|FALSE
5300|"          Above, below, appeared angelic charms;"|FALSE
5300|"          'Twas Paradise, 'twas Heav'n, within her arms!"|FALSE
5300|"          THE Gascon was--a Gascon;--would you more?"|FALSE
5300|"          Who knows a Gascon knows at least a score."|FALSE
5300|"          I need not say what solemn vows he made;"|FALSE
5300|"          Alike with Normans Gascons are portrayed;"|FALSE
5300|"          Their oaths, indeed, won't pass for Gospel truth;"|FALSE
5300|"          But we believe that Dorilas (the youth)"|FALSE
5300|"          Loved Phillis to his soul, our lady fair,"|FALSE
5300|"          Yet he would fain be thought successful there."|FALSE
5300|"          ONE day, said Phillis, with unusual glee,"|FALSE
5300|"          Pretending with the Gascon to be free:--"|FALSE
5300|"          A favour do me:--nothing very great;"|FALSE
5300|"          Assist to dupe one jealous of his mate;"|FALSE
5300|"          You'll find it very easy to be done,"|FALSE
5300|"          And doubtless 'twill produce a deal of fun."|FALSE
