5300|"          Through pity, she at last, to please the chief,"|FALSE
5300|"          Consented to bestow on him relief;"|FALSE
5300|"          For, favours, when conferred with sullen air,"|FALSE
5300|"          But little gratify she was aware."|FALSE
5300|"          WHen satisfied the smart gallant appeared,"|FALSE
5300|"          And anxiously to putting off adhered,"|FALSE
5300|"          Pretending that the wind and tide would fail;"|FALSE
5300|"          The galleys sometimes were unfit to sail,"|FALSE
5300|"          Repairs required; then further heard the news,"|FALSE
5300|"          That certain pirates had unpleasant views;"|FALSE
5300|"          To fall upon the escort they'd contrived:"|FALSE
5300|"          At length, a pirate suddenly arrived,"|FALSE
5300|"          Surprized the party left upon the shore,"|FALSE
5300|"          Destroyed the whole; then sought the house for more,"|FALSE
5300|"          And scaled the walls while darkness spread around."|FALSE
5300|"          The pirate was Grifonio's second found,"|FALSE
5300|"          Who, in a trice, the noble mansion took,"|FALSE
5300|"          And joy gave place to grief in ev'ry look."|FALSE
5300|"          THe Alexandrian swore and cursed his lot;"|FALSE
5300|"          The pirate soon the lady's story got,"|FALSE
5300|"          And, taking her aside, his share required"|FALSE
5300|"          Such impudence Alaciel's patience tired,"|FALSE
5300|"          Who, ev'ry thing refused with haughty air;"|FALSE
5300|"          Of this, howe'er, the robber was aware;"|FALSE
5300|"          In Venus' court no novice was he thought;"|FALSE
5300|"          To gain the princess anxiously he sought;"|FALSE
5300|"          Said he, you'd better take me as a friend;"|FALSE
5300|"          I'm more than pirate, and you'll comprehend,"|FALSE
5300|"          As you've obliged one dying swain to fast,"|FALSE
5300|"          You fast in turn, or you'll give way at last;"|FALSE
5300|"          'Tis justice this demands: we sons of sea"|FALSE
5300|"          Know how to deal with those of each degree;"|FALSE
5300|"          Remember you will nothing have to eat,"|FALSE
5300|"          Till your surrender fully is complete."|FALSE
5300|"          NO haggling, princess pray, my word receive;"|FALSE
5300|"          What could be done, her terror to relieve?"|FALSE
5300|"          Above all law is might:--'twill take its course;"|FALSE
5300|"          Entire submission is the last resource."|FALSE
5300|"          OF'T what we would not, we're obliged to do,"|FALSE
5300|"          When fate our steps with rigour will pursue."|FALSE
5300|"          No folly greater than to heighten pain,"|FALSE
5300|"          When we are sensible relief is vain."|FALSE
5300|"          What she, through pity, to another gave,"|FALSE
5300|"          Might well be granted when herself 'twould save."|FALSE
5300|"          AT length she yielded to this suitor rude:--"|FALSE
5300|"          No grief so great, but what may be subdued."|FALSE
5300|"          'Twould in the pirate doubtless have been wise,"|FALSE
5300|"          The belle to move, and thus prevent surprise;"|FALSE
5300|"          But who, from folly in amours is free?"|FALSE
5300|"          The god of love and wisdom ne'er agree."|FALSE
5300|"          WHILE our gay pirate thought himself at ease,"|FALSE
5300|"          The wind quite fair to sail when he might please,"|FALSE
5300|"          Dame Fortune, sleepy only while we wake,"|FALSE
5300|"          And slily watching when repose we take,"|FALSE
5300|"          Contrived a trick the cunning knave to play,"|FALSE
5300|"          And this was put in force ere break of day."|FALSE
5300|"          A LORD, the owner of a neighb'ring seat,"|FALSE
5300|"          Unmarried;--fond of what was nice and neat,"|FALSE
5300|"          Without attachment, and devoid of care,"|FALSE
5300|"          Save something new to meet among the FAIR;"|FALSE
5300|"          Grew tired of those he long around had viewed,"|FALSE
5300|"          Now constantly, in thought, our belle pursued."|FALSE
5300|"          He'd money, friends, and credit all his days,"|FALSE
5300|"          And could two thousand men at pleasure raise:"|FALSE
5300|"          One charming morn, together these he brought;"|FALSE
5300|"          Said he, brave fellows, can it well be thought,"|FALSE
5300|"          That we allow a pirate, (dire disgrace!)"|FALSE
5300|"          To plunder as he likes before our face,"|FALSE
5300|"          And make a slave of one whose form 's divine?"|FALSE
5300|"          Let's to the castle, such is my design,"|FALSE
5300|"          And from the ruffian liberate the fair;"|FALSE
5300|"          This evening ev'ry one will here repair,"|FALSE
5300|"          Well armed, and then in silence we'll proceed,"|FALSE
5300|"          (By night 'tis nothing will impede,)"|FALSE
5300|"          And ere Aurora peeps, perform the task;"|FALSE
5300|"          The only booty that I mean to ask"|FALSE
5300|"          Is this fair dame; but not a slave to make,"|FALSE
5300|"          I anxiously desire to let her take"|FALSE
5300|"          Whate'er is her's:--restore her honour too;"|FALSE
5300|"          All other things I freely leave to you;"|FALSE
5300|"          Men, horses, baggage, in a word, the whole"|FALSE
5300|"          Of what the knavish rascals now control."|FALSE
5300|"          Another thing, howe'er:--I wish to hang"|FALSE
5300|"          The pirate instantly, before his gang."|FALSE
5300|"          THIS speech so well succeeded to inspire,"|FALSE
5300|"          That scarcely could the men retain their ire."|FALSE
5300|"          THE evening came, the party soon arrived;"|FALSE
5300|"          They ate not much, but drink their rage revived."|FALSE
5300|"          By such expensive treats we've armies known,"|FALSE
5300|"          In Germany and Flanders overthrown;"|FALSE
5300|"          And our commander was of this aware"|FALSE
5300|"          'Twas prudent, surely, no expense to spare."|FALSE
5300|"          THEY carried ladders for the escalade,"|FALSE
5300|"          And each was furnished with a tempered blade;"|FALSE
5300|"          No other thing embarrassing they'd got;"|FALSE
5300|"          No drums; but all was silent as the grot."|FALSE
5300|"          THEY reached the house when nearly break of day,"|FALSE
5300|"          The time old Morpheus' slumbers often weigh;"|FALSE
5300|"          The gang, with few exceptions, (then asleep),"|FALSE
5300|"          Were sent, their vigils with grim death to keep."|FALSE
5300|"          THE chief hung up:--the princess soon appeared;"|FALSE
5300|"          Her spirits presently our champion cheered;"|FALSE
5300|"          The pirate scarcely had her bosom moved:--"|FALSE
5300|"          No tears at least a marked affection proved;"|FALSE
5300|"          But, by her prayers she pardon sought to gain,"|FALSE
5300|"          For some who were not in the conflict slain;"|FALSE
5300|"          Consoled the dying, and lamented those,"|FALSE
5300|"          Who, by the sword, had closed their book of woes:"|FALSE
5300|"          Then left the place without the least regret,"|FALSE
5300|"          Where such adventures and alarms she'd met."|FALSE
5300|"          'Tis said, indeed, she presently forgot"|FALSE
5300|"          The two gallants who last became her lot;"|FALSE
5300|"          And I can easily the fact believe:"|FALSE
5300|"          Removed from sight, but few for lovers grieve."|FALSE
5300|"          SHE, by her neighbour, was received, we're told,"|FALSE
5300|"          'Mid costly furniture and burnished gold;"|FALSE
5300|"          We may suppose what splendour shone around,"|FALSE
5300|"          When all-attracting he would fain be found;"|FALSE
5300|"          The best of wines; each dish considered rare:--"|FALSE
5300|"          The gods themselves received not better fare:"|FALSE
5300|"          Till then, Alaciel ne'er had tasted wine;"|FALSE
5300|"          Her faith forbade a liquor so divine;"|FALSE
5300|"          And, unacquainted with the potent juice,"|FALSE
5300|"          She much indulged at table in its use."|FALSE
5300|"          If lately LOVE disquieted her brain,"|FALSE
5300|"          New poison now pervaded ev'ry vein;"|FALSE
5300|"          Both fraught with danger to the beauteous FAIR,"|FALSE
5300|"          Whose charms should guarded be with ev'ry care."|FALSE
5300|"          THE princess by the maids in bed was placed;"|FALSE
5300|"          Then thither went the host with anxious haste,"|FALSE
5300|"          What sought he? you will ask:--mere torpid charms:--"|FALSE
5300|"          I wish the like were clasped within my arms."|FALSE
5300|"          Give me as much, said one the other week,"|FALSE
5300|"          And see if I'd a neighbour's kindness seek."|FALSE
5300|"          Through Morpheus' sleepy pow'r, and Bacchus' wine:"|FALSE
5300|"          Our host, at length, completed his design."|FALSE
5300|"          ALACIEL, when at morn, she oped her eyes,"|FALSE
5300|"          Was quite o'ercome with terror and surprise,"|FALSE
5300|"          No tears would flow, and fear restrained her voice;"|FALSE
5300|"          Unable to resist, she'd got no choice."|FALSE
5300|"          A NIGHT thus passed, the wily lover said,"|FALSE
5300|"          Must surely give a license to your bed."|FALSE
5300|"          The princess thought the same; but our gallant,"|FALSE
5300|"          Soon cloyed, for other conquests 'gan to pant."|FALSE
5300|"          THE host one evening from the mansion went;"|FALSE
5300|"          A friend he left himself to represent,"|FALSE
5300|"          And with the charming fair supply his place,"|FALSE
5300|"          Which, in the dark he thought, with easy grace,"|FALSE
5300|"          Might be effected, if he held his tongue,"|FALSE
5300|"          And properly behaved the whole night long."|FALSE
5300|"          To this the other willingly agreed;"|FALSE
5300|"          (What friend would be refused, if thus in need?)"|FALSE
5300|"          And this new-comer had complete success"|FALSE
5300|"          He scarcely could his ecstacy express."|FALSE
5300|"          THE dame exclaimed:--pray how could he pretend;"|FALSE
5300|"          To treat me so, and leave me to a friend?"|FALSE
5300|"          The other thought the host was much to blame;"|FALSE
5300|"          But since 'tis o'er, said he, be now your aim,"|FALSE
5300|"          To punish his contempt of beauteous charms;"|FALSE
5300|"          With favours load me--take me to your arms;"|FALSE
5300|"          Caress with fond embrace; bestow delight;"|FALSE
5300|"          And seem to love me, though in mere despite."|FALSE
5300|"          SHE followed his advice: avenged the wrong;"|FALSE
5300|"          And naught omitted, pleasures to prolong."|FALSE
5300|"          If he obtained his wishes from the fair,"|FALSE
5300|"          The host about it scarcely seemed to care."|FALSE
5300|"          THE sixth adventure of our charming belle,"|FALSE
5300|"          Some writers one way, some another tell;"|FALSE
5300|"          Whence many think that favour I have shown,"|FALSE
5300|"          And for her, one gallant the less would own."|FALSE
5300|"          Mere scandal this; from truth I would nor swerve,"|FALSE
5300|"          To please the fair: more credence I deserve;"|FALSE
5300|"          Her husband only eight precursors had;"|FALSE
5300|"          The fact was such;--I none suppress nor add."|FALSE
5300|"          THE host returned and found his friend content;"|FALSE
5300|"          To pardon him Alaciel gave consent;"|FALSE
5300|"          And 'tween them things would equally divide"|FALSE
5300|"          Of royal bosoms clemency's the pride."|FALSE
5300|"          WHILE thus the princess passed from hand to hand"|FALSE
5300|"          She oft amused her fancy 'mong a band"|FALSE
5300|"          Of charming belles that on her would attend,"|FALSE
5300|"          And one of these she made an humble friend."|FALSE
5300|"          The fav'rite in the house a lover had,"|FALSE
5300|"          A smart, engaging, handsome, clever lad,"|FALSE
5300|"          Well born, but much to violence inclined"|FALSE
5300|"          A wooer that could scarcely be confined"|FALSE
5300|"          To gentle means, but oft his suit began,"|FALSE
5300|"          Where others end, who follow Cupid's plan."|FALSE
5300|"          IT one day happened, that this forward spark;"|FALSE
5300|"          The girl we speak of, met within the park,"|FALSE
5300|"          And to a summer-house the fav'rite drew;"|FALSE
5300|"          The course they took the princess chanced to view"|FALSE
5300|"          As wand'ring near; but neither swain nor fair,"|FALSE
5300|"          Suspicion had, that any one was there;"|FALSE
5300|"          And this gallant most confidently thought,"|FALSE
5300|"          The girl by force, might to his terms be brought!"|FALSE
5300|"          His wretched temper, obstacle to love,"|FALSE
5300|"          And ev'ry bliss bestowed by heav'n above,"|FALSE
5300|"          Had oft his hopes of favours lately marred;"|FALSE
5300|"          And fear, with those designs, had also jarred:"|FALSE
5300|"          The girl, howe'er, would likely have been kind,"|FALSE
5300|"          If opportunities had pleased her mind."|FALSE
5300|"          THE lover, now convinced that he was feared;"|FALSE
5300|"          In dark designs upon her persevered."|FALSE
5300|"          No sooner had she entered, than our man"|FALSE
5300|"          Locked instantly the door, but vain his plan;"|FALSE
5300|"          To open it the princess had a key;"|FALSE
5300|"          The girl her fault perceived, and tried to flee;"|FALSE
5300|"          He held her fast; the charmer loudly called;"|FALSE
5300|"          The princess came--or vainly she had squalled."|FALSE
5300|"          QUITE disappointed: overcome with ire,"|FALSE
5300|"          He wholly lost respect amid desire,"|FALSE
5300|"          And swore by all the gods, that, ere they went,"|FALSE
5300|"          The one or other should to him consent;"|FALSE
5300|"          Their hands he'd firmly tie to have his way;"|FALSE
5300|"          For help (the place so far) 'twere vain to pray;"|FALSE
5300|"          To take a lot was all that he'd allow;"|FALSE
5300|"          Come, draw, he said; to Fortune you must bow;"|FALSE
5300|"          No haggling I request--comply; be still:"|FALSE
5300|"          Resolved I am with one to have my will."|FALSE
5300|"          WHAT has the princess done? the girl replied,"|FALSE
5300|"          That you, to make her suffer, thus decide"|FALSE
5300|"          Yes, said the spark, if on her fall the lot,"|FALSE
5300|"          Then you'll, at least for present, be forgot."|FALSE
5300|"          NO, cried Alaciel, ne'er I'll have it said,"|FALSE
5300|"          To sacrifice I saw a maiden led;"|FALSE
5300|"          I'll suffer rather all that you expect,"|FALSE
5300|"          If you will spare my friend as I direct."|FALSE
5300|"          'Twas all in vain, the lots were drawn at last,"|FALSE
5300|"          And on the princess was the burthen cast;"|FALSE
5300|"          The other was permitted to retire,"|FALSE
5300|"          And each was sworn that nothing should transpire:"|FALSE
5300|"          But our gallant would sooner have been hung,"|FALSE
5300|"          Than have upon such secrets held his tongue;"|FALSE
5300|"          'Tis clear, no longer silent he remained,"|FALSE
5300|"          Than one to listen to his tale he'd gained."|FALSE
5300|"          THIS change of favourites the princess grieved;"|FALSE
5300|"          That Cupid trifled with her she perceived;"|FALSE
5300|"          With much regret she saw her blooming charms,"|FALSE
5300|"          The Helen of too many Paris' arms."|FALSE
5300|"          ONE day it happened, as our beauteous belle"|FALSE
5300|"          Was sleeping in a wood beside a dell,"|FALSE
5300|"          By chance there passed, quite near, a wand'ring knight,"|FALSE
5300|"          Like those the ladies followed with delight,"|FALSE
5300|"          When they on palfreys rode in days of old,"|FALSE
5300|"          And purity were always thought to hold."|FALSE
5300|"          THIS knight, who copied those of famed romance,"|FALSE
5300|"          Sir Roger, and the rest, in complisance,"|FALSE
5300|"          No sooner saw the princess thus asleep,"|FALSE
5300|"          Than instantly he wished a kiss to reap."|FALSE
5300|"          While thinking, whether from the neck or lip,"|FALSE
5300|"          'Twere best the tempting balm of bliss to sip,"|FALSE
5300|"          He suddenly began to recollect"|FALSE
5300|"          The laws of chivalry he should respect."|FALSE
5300|"          Although the thought retained, his fervent prayer"|FALSE
5300|"          To Cupid was, that while the nymph was there,"|FALSE
5300|"          Her fascinating charms he might enjoy;"|FALSE
5300|"          Sure love's soft senses were ne'er designed to cloy!"|FALSE
5300|"          THE princess woke, and great surprise expressed;"|FALSE
5300|"          Oh! charming fair, said he, be not distressed;"|FALSE
5300|"          No savage of the woods nor giant 's nigh,"|FALSE
5300|"          A wand'ring knight alone you now descry,"|FALSE
5300|"          Delighted thus to meet a beauteous belle"|FALSE
5300|"          Such charms divine, what angel can excel!"|FALSE
5300|"          THIS compliment was followed by his sighs,"|FALSE
5300|"          And frank confession, both from tongue and eyes;"|FALSE
5300|"          Our lover far in little time could go;"|FALSE
5300|"          At length, he offered on her to bestow,"|FALSE
5300|"          His hand and heart, and ev'ry thing beside,"|FALSE
5300|"          Which custom sanctions when we seek a bride."|FALSE
5300|"          WITH courtesy his offer was received,"|FALSE
5300|"          And she related what her bosom grieved;"|FALSE
5300|"          Detailed her hist'ry, but with care concealed"|FALSE
5300|"          The six gallants, as wrong to be revealed."|FALSE
5300|"          The knight, in what he wished, indulgence got;"|FALSE
5300|"          And, while the princess much deplored her lot,"|FALSE
5300|"          The youth proposed Alaciel he should bring,"|FALSE
5300|"          To Mamolin, or Alexandria's king."|FALSE
5300|"          TO Mamolin? replied the princess fair,"|FALSE
5300|"          No, no--I now indeed would fain repair,"|FALSE
5300|"          (Could I my wishes have), to Zarus' court,"|FALSE
5300|"          My native country:--thither give support."|FALSE
5300|"          IF Cupid grant me life, rejoined the knight,"|FALSE
5300|"          You there shall go, and I'll assist your flight;"|FALSE
5300|"          To have redress, upon yourself depends,"|FALSE
5300|"          As well as to requite the best of friends;"|FALSE
5300|"          But should I perish in the bold design,"|FALSE
5300|"          Submit you must, as wills the pow'rs divine."|FALSE
5300|"          I'll freely say, howe'er, that I regard,"|FALSE
5300|"          My services enough to claim reward."|FALSE
5300|"          ALACIEL readily to this agreed;"|FALSE
5300|"          And favours fondly promised to concede;"|FALSE
5300|"          T'ensure, indeed, his guarding her throughout,"|FALSE
5300|"          They were to be conferred upon the route,"|FALSE
5300|"          From time to time as onward they should go,"|FALSE
5300|"          Not all at once, but daily some to flow."|FALSE
5300|"          THINGS thus arranged, the fair behind the knight"|FALSE
5300|"          Got up at once, and with him took to flight."|FALSE
5300|"          Our cavalier his servants sought to find,"|FALSE
5300|"          That, when he crossed the wood, he left behind;"|FALSE
5300|"          With these a nephew and his tutor rode;"|FALSE
5300|"          The belle a palfrey took, as more the mode,"|FALSE
5300|"          But, by her walked attentively the spark,"|FALSE
5300|"          A tale he'd now relate; at times remark"|FALSE
5300|"          The passing scene; then press his ardent flame;"|FALSE
5300|"          And thus amused our royal, beauteous dame."|FALSE
5300|"          THE treaty was most faithfully observed;"|FALSE
5300|"          No calculation wrong; from naught they swerved."|FALSE
5300|"          At length they reached the sea; on ship-board got;"|FALSE
5300|"          A quick and pleasing passage was their lot;"|FALSE
5300|"          Delightfully serene, which joy increased;"|FALSE
5300|"          To land they came (from perils thought released;)"|FALSE
5300|"          At Joppa they debarked; two days remained:"|FALSE
5300|"          And when refreshed, the proper road they gained;"|FALSE
5300|"          Their escort was the lover's train alone;"|FALSE
5300|"          On Asia's shores to plunder bands are prone;"|FALSE
5300|"          By these were met our spark and lovely fair;"|FALSE
5300|"          New dangers they, alas! were forced to share."|FALSE
5300|"          TO cede, at first, their numbers forced the train;"|FALSE
5300|"          But rallied by our knight they were again;"|FALSE
5300|"          A desp'rate push he made; repulsed their force;"|FALSE
5300|"          And by his valour stopt, at length, their course;"|FALSE
5300|"          In which attack a mortal wound he got,"|FALSE
5300|"          But was not left for dead upon the spot."|FALSE
5300|"          BEFORE his death he full instructions gave,"|FALSE
5300|"          To grant the belle whatever she might crave;"|FALSE
5300|"          He ordered too, his nephew should convey,"|FALSE
5300|"          Alaciel to her home without delay,"|FALSE
5300|"          Bequeathing him whatever he possessed,"|FALSE
5300|"          And--what the princess owed among the rest."|FALSE
5300|"          AT length, from dread alarms and tears released,"|FALSE
5300|"          The pair fulfilled the will of our deceased;"|FALSE
5300|"          Discharged each favour was, of which the last"|FALSE
5300|"          Was cancelled just as they the frontiers passed."|FALSE
5300|"          THE nephew here his precious charge resigned,"|FALSE
5300|"          For fear the king should be displeased to find,"|FALSE
5300|"          His daughter guarded by a youthful swain:--"|FALSE
5300|"          The tutor only with her could remain."|FALSE
5300|"          NO words of mine, no language can express"|FALSE
5300|"          The monarch's joy his child to re-possess;"|FALSE
5300|"          And, since the difficulty I perceive,"|FALSE
5300|"          I'll imitate old Sol's retreat at eve,"|FALSE
5300|"          Who falls with such rapidity of view,"|FALSE
5300|"          He seems to plunge, dame Thetis to pursue."|FALSE
5300|"          THE tutor liked his own details to hear,"|FALSE
5300|"          And entertaining made his tales appear:"|FALSE
5300|"          The num'rous perils that the fair had fled,"|FALSE
5300|"          Who laughed aside, no doubt, at what he said."|FALSE
5300|"          I SHOULD observe, the aged tutor cried,"|FALSE
5300|"          The princess, while for liberty she sighed,"|FALSE
5300|"          And quite alone remained (by Hispal left,)"|FALSE
5300|"          That she might be of idleness bereft,"|FALSE
5300|"          Resolved most fervently a god to serve,"|FALSE
5300|"          From whom she scarcely since would ever swerve,"|FALSE
5300|"          A god much worshipped 'mong the people there,"|FALSE
5300|"          With num'rous temples which his honours share,"|FALSE
5300|"          Denominated cabinets and bow'rs,"|FALSE
5300|"          In which, from high respect to heav'nly pow'rs,"|FALSE
5300|"          They represent the image of a bird,"|FALSE
5300|"          A pleasing sight, though (what appears absurd)"|FALSE
5300|"          'Tis bare of plumage, save about the wings;"|FALSE
5300|"          To this each youthful bosom incense brings,"|FALSE
5300|"          While other gods, as I've been often told,"|FALSE
5300|"          They scarcely notice, till they're growing old."|FALSE
5300|"          DID you but know the virtuous steps she trod,"|FALSE
5300|"          While thus devoted to the little god,"|FALSE
5300|"          You'd thank a hundred times the pow'rs above,"|FALSE
5300|"          That gave you such a child to bless your love."|FALSE
5300|"          But many other customs there abound:--"|FALSE
5300|"          The FAIR with perfect liberty are found:"|FALSE
5300|"          Can go and come, whene'er the humour fits;"|FALSE
5300|"          No eunuch (shadow like) that never quits;"|FALSE
5300|"          But watches ev'ry movement:--always feared;"|FALSE
5300|"          No men, but who've upon the chin a beard:"|FALSE
5300|"          Your daughter from the first, their manners took:"|FALSE
5300|"          So easy is her ev'ry act and look,"|FALSE
5300|"          And truly to her honour I may say,"|FALSE
5300|"          She's all-accommodating ev'ry way."|FALSE
5300|"          THE king delighted seemed at what he heard;"|FALSE
5300|"          But since her journey could not be deferred,"|FALSE
5300|"          The princess, with a num'rous escort, tried"|FALSE
5300|"          Again o'er seas t'wards Garba's shores to glide,"|FALSE
5300|"          And, there arrived, was cordially received"|FALSE
5300|"          By Mamolin, who loved, she soon believed,"|FALSE
5300|"          To fond excess; and, all her suite to aid,"|FALSE
5300|"          A handsome gift to ev'ry one was made."|FALSE
5300|"          THE king with noble feasts the court regaled,"|FALSE
5300|"          At which Alaciel pleasantly detailed"|FALSE
5300|"          just what she liked, or true or false, 'twas clear;"|FALSE
5300|"          The prince and courtiers were disposed to hear."|FALSE
5300|"          AT night the queen retired to soft repose,"|FALSE
5300|"          From whence next morn with honour she arose;"|FALSE
5300|"          The king was found much pleasure to express;"|FALSE
5300|"          Alaciel asked no more, you well may guess."|FALSE
5300|"          BY this we learn, that husbands who aver"|FALSE
5300|"          Their wond'rous penetration often err;"|FALSE
5300|"          And while they fancy things so very plain,"|FALSE
5300|"          They've been preceded by a fav'rite swain."|FALSE
5300|"          The safest rule 's to be upon your guard;"|FALSE
5300|"          Fear ev'ry guile; yet hope the full reward."|FALSE
5300|"          SWEET, charming FAIR, your characters revere;"|FALSE
5300|"          The Mamolin's a bird not common here."|FALSE
5300|"          With us Love's fascination is so soon"|FALSE
5300|"          Succeeded by the licensed honey moon,"|FALSE
5300|"          There's scarcely opportunity to fool,"|FALSE
5300|"          Though oft the husband proves an easy tool."|FALSE
5300|"          YOUR friendships may be very chaste and pure,"|FALSE
5300|"          But strangely Cupid's lessons will allure."|FALSE
5300|"          Defeat his wiles; resist his tempting charms"|FALSE
5300|"          E'en from suspicion suffer not alarms."|FALSE
5300|"          Don't laugh at my advice; 'twere like the boys,"|FALSE
5300|"          Who better might amuse themselves with toys."|FALSE
5300|"          IF any one, howe'er unable seem,"|FALSE
5300|"          To make resistance 'gainst the flame supreme"|FALSE
5300|"          Turn ALL to jest; though right to keep the crown"|FALSE
5300|"          Yet lost, 'there wrong, yourself to hang or drown."|FALSE
5300|"                     THE MAGICK CUP"|FALSE
5300|"          THE worst of ills, with jealousy compared,"|FALSE
5300|"          Are trifling torments ev'ry where declared."|FALSE
5300|"          IMAGINE, to yourself a silly fool,"|FALSE
5300|"          To dark suspicion grown an easy tool;"|FALSE
5300|"          No soft repose he finds, by night or day;"|FALSE
5300|"          But rings his ear, he's wretched ev'ry way!"|FALSE
5300|"          Continually he dreams his forehead sprouts;"|FALSE
5300|"          The truth of reveries he never doubts."|FALSE
5300|"          But this I would not fully guaranty,"|FALSE
5300|"          For he who dreams, 'tis said, asleep should be;"|FALSE
5300|"          And those who've caught, from time to time, a peep,"|FALSE
5300|"          Pretend to say--the jealous never sleep."|FALSE
5300|"          A MAN who has suspicions soon will rouse;"|FALSE
5300|"          But buz a fly around his precious spouse,"|FALSE
5300|"          At once he fancies cuckoldom is brought,"|FALSE
5300|"          And nothing can eradicate the thought;"|FALSE
5300|"          In spite of reason he must have a place,"|FALSE
5300|"          And numbered be, among the horned race;"|FALSE
5300|"          A cuckold to himself he freely owns,"|FALSE
5300|"          Though otherwise perhaps in flesh and bones."|FALSE
5300|"          GOOD folks, of cuckoldom, pray what's the harm,"|FALSE
5300|"          To give, from time to time, such dire alarm?"|FALSE
5300|"          What injury 's received, and what 's the wrong,"|FALSE
5300|"          At which so many sneer and loll their tongue?"|FALSE
5300|"          While unacquainted with the fact, 'tis naught;"|FALSE
5300|"          If known:--e'en then 'tis scarcely worth a thought."|FALSE
5300|"          You think, however, 'tis a serious grief;"|FALSE
5300|"          Then try to doubt it, which may bring relief,"|FALSE
5300|"          And don't resemble him who took a sup,"|FALSE
5300|"          From out the celebrated magick cup."|FALSE
5300|"          Be warned by others' ills; the tale I'll tell;"|FALSE
5300|"          Perhaps your irksomeness it may dispel."|FALSE
5300|"          BUT first, by reason let me prove, I pray,"|FALSE
5300|"          That evil such as this, and which you say,"|FALSE
5300|"          Oft weighs you down with soul-corroding care;"|FALSE
5300|"          Is only in the mind:--mere spright of air:"|FALSE
5300|"          Your hat upon your head for instance place,"|FALSE
5300|"          Less gently rather than's your usual case;"|FALSE
5300|"          Pray, don't it presently at ease remain?"|FALSE
5300|"          And from it do you aught amiss retain?"|FALSE
5300|"          Not e'en a spot; there's nothing half so clear;"|FALSE
5300|"          The features, too, they as before appear?"|FALSE
5300|"          No difference assuredly you see?"|FALSE
5300|"          Then how can cuckoldom an evil be?"|FALSE
5300|"          Such my conclusion, spite of fools or brutes,"|FALSE
5300|"          With whose ideas reason never suits."|FALSE
5300|"          YES, yes, but honour has, you know, a claim:"|FALSE
5300|"          Who e'er denied it?--never 'twas my aim."|FALSE
5300|"          But what of honour?--nothing else is heard;"|FALSE
5300|"          At Rome a different conduct is preferred;"|FALSE
5300|"          The cuckold there, who takes the thing to heart,"|FALSE
5300|"          Is thought a fool, and acts a blockhead's part;"|FALSE
5300|"          While he, who laughs, is always well received"|FALSE
5300|"          And honest fellow through the town believed."|FALSE
5300|"          Were this misfortune viewed with proper eyes,"|FALSE
5300|"          Such ills from cuckoldom would ne'er arise."|FALSE
5300|"          THAT advantageous 'tis, we now will prove:"|FALSE
5300|"          Folks laugh; your wife a pliant glove shall move;"|FALSE
5300|"          But, if you've twenty favourites around,"|FALSE
5300|"          A single syllable will ne'er resound."|FALSE
5300|"          Whene'er you speak, each word has double force;"|FALSE
5300|"          At table, you've precedency of course,"|FALSE
5300|"          And oft will get the very nicest parts;"|FALSE
5300|"          Well pleased who serves you!--all the household smarts"|FALSE
5300|"          No means neglect your favour to obtain;"|FALSE
5300|"          You've full command; resistance would be vain."|FALSE
5300|"          Whence this conclusion must directly spring:"|FALSE
5300|"          To be a cuckold is a useful thing."|FALSE
5300|"          AT cards, should adverse fortune you pursue;"|FALSE
5300|"          To take revenge is ever thought your due;"|FALSE
5300|"          And your opponent often will revoke,"|FALSE
5300|"          That you for better luck may have a cloak:"|FALSE
5300|"          If you've a friend o'er head and ears in debt:"|FALSE
5300|"          At once, to help him numbers you can get."|FALSE
5300|"          You fancy these your rind regales and cheers"|FALSE
5300|"          She's better for it; more beautiful appears;"|FALSE
5300|"          The Spartan king, in Helen found new charms,"|FALSE
5300|"          When he'd recovered her from Paris' arms."|FALSE
5300|"          YOUR wife the same; to make her, in your eye,"|FALSE
5300|"          More beautiful 's the aim you may rely;"|FALSE
5300|"          For, if unkind, she would a hag be thought,"|FALSE
5300|"          Incapable soft love scenes to be taught."|FALSE
5300|"          These reasons make me to my thesis cling,--"|FALSE
5300|"          To be a cuckold is a useful thing."|FALSE
5300|"          IF much too long this introduction seem,"|FALSE
5300|"          The obvious cause is clearly in the theme,"|FALSE
5300|"          And should not certainly be hurried o'er,"|FALSE
5300|"          But now for something from th' historick store."|FALSE
5300|"          A CERTAIN man, no matter for his name,"|FALSE
5300|"          His country, rank, nor residence nor fame,"|FALSE
5300|"          Through fear of accidents had firmly sworn,"|FALSE
5300|"          The marriage chain should ne'er by him be worn;"|FALSE
5300|"          No tie but friendship, from the sex he'd crave:"|FALSE
5300|"          If wrong or right, the question we will wave."|FALSE
5300|"          Be this as 't will, since Hymen could not find"|FALSE
5300|"          Our wight to bear the wedded knot inclined,"|FALSE
5300|"          The god of love, to manage for him tried,"|FALSE
5300|"          And what he wished, from time to time supplied;"|FALSE
5300|"          A lively fair he got, who charms displayed,"|FALSE
5300|"          And made him father to a little maid;"|FALSE
5300|"          Then died, and left the spark dissolved in tears:"|FALSE
5300|"          Not such as flow for wives, (as oft appears)"|FALSE
5300|"          When mourning 's nothing more than change of dress:"|FALSE
5300|"          His anguish spoke the soul in great distress."|FALSE
5300|"          THE daughter grew in years, improved in mien,"|FALSE
5300|"          And soon the woman in her air was seen;"|FALSE
5300|"          Time rolls apace, and once she's ridded of her bib,"|FALSE
5300|"          Then alters daily, and her tongue gets glib,"|FALSE
5300|"          Each year still taller, till she's found at length;"|FALSE
5300|"          A perfect belle in look, in age, in strength."|FALSE
5300|"          His forward child, the father justly feared,"|FALSE
5300|"          Would cheat the priest of fees so much revered;"|FALSE
5300|"          The lawyer too, and god of marriage-joys;"|FALSE
5300|"          Sad fault, that future prospects oft destroys:"|FALSE
5300|"          To trust her virtue was not quite so sure;"|FALSE
5300|"          He chose a convent, to be more secure,"|FALSE
5300|"          Where this young charmer learned to pray and sew;"|FALSE
5300|"          No wicked books, unfit for girls to know,"|FALSE
5300|"          Corruption's page the senses to beguile"|FALSE
5300|"          Dan Cupid never writes in convent style:"|FALSE
5300|"          OF nothing would she talk but holy-writ;"|FALSE
5300|"          On which she could herself so well acquit,"|FALSE
5300|"          That oft the gravest teachers were confused;"|FALSE
5300|"          To praise her beauty, scarcely was excused;"|FALSE
5300|"          No flatt'ry pleasure gave, and she'd reply:"|FALSE
5300|"          Good sister stay!--consider, we must die;"|FALSE
5300|"          Each feature perishes:--'tis naught but clay;"|FALSE
5300|"          And soon will worms upon our bodies prey:"|FALSE
5300|"          Superior needle-work our fair could do;"|FALSE
5300|"          The spindle turn at ease:--embroider too;"|FALSE
5300|"          Minerva's skill, or Clotho's, could impart;"|FALSE
5300|"          In tapestry she'd gained Arachne's art;"|FALSE
5300|"          And other talents, too, the daughter showed;"|FALSE
5300|"          Her sense, wealth, beauty, soon were spread abroad:"|FALSE
5300|"          But most her wealth a marked attention drew;"|FALSE
5300|"          The belle had been immured with prudent view,"|FALSE
5300|"          To keep her safely till a spouse was found,"|FALSE
5300|"          Who with sufficient riches should abound."|FALSE
5300|"          From convents, heiresses are often led"|FALSE
5300|"          Directly to the altar to be wed."|FALSE
5300|"          SOME time the father had the girl declared"|FALSE
5300|"          His lawful child, who all his fondness shared."|FALSE
5300|"          As soon as she was free from convent walls,"|FALSE
5300|"          Her taste at once was changed from books to balls;"|FALSE
5300|"          Around Calista (such was named our fair)"|FALSE
5300|"          A host of lovers showed attentive care;"|FALSE
5300|"          Cits, courtiers, officers, the beau, the sage,"|FALSE
5300|"          Adventurers of ev'ry rank and age."|FALSE
5300|"          FROM these Calista presently made choice,"|FALSE
5300|"          Of one for whom her father gave his voice;"|FALSE
5300|"          A handsome lad, and thought good humoured too"|FALSE
5300|"          Few otherwise appear when first they woo."|FALSE
5300|"          Her fortune ample was; the dow'r the same;"|FALSE
5300|"          The belle an only child; the like her flame."|FALSE
5300|"          But better still, our couple's chief delight,"|FALSE
5300|"          Was mutual love and pleasure to excite."|FALSE
5300|"          TWO years in paradise thus passed the pair,"|FALSE
5300|"          When bliss was changed to Hell's worst cank'ring care;"|FALSE
5300|"          A fit of jealousy the husband grieved,"|FALSE
5300|"          And, strange to tell, he all at once believed,"|FALSE
5300|"          A lover with success his wife addressed,"|FALSE
5300|"          When, but for him, the suit had ne'er been pressed;"|FALSE
5300|"          For though the spark, the charming fair to gain,"|FALSE
5300|"          Would ev'ry wily method try, 'twas plain,"|FALSE
5300|"          Yet had the husband never terrors shown,"|FALSE
5300|"          The lover, in despair, had quickly flown."|FALSE
5300|"          WHAT should a husband do whose wife is sought,"|FALSE
5300|"          With anxious fondness by another? Naught."|FALSE
5300|"          'Tis this that leads me ever to advise,"|FALSE
5300|"          To sleep at ease whichever side he lies."|FALSE
5300|"          In case she lends the spark a willing ear,"|FALSE
5300|"          'Twill not be better if you interfere:"|FALSE
5300|"          She'll seek more opportunities you'll find;"|FALSE
5300|"          But if to pay attention she's inclined,"|FALSE
5300|"          You'll raise the inclination in her brain,"|FALSE
5300|"          And then the danger will begin again."|FALSE
5300|"          WHERE'ER suspicion dwells you may be sure,"|FALSE
5300|"          To cuckoldom 'twill prove a place secure."|FALSE
5300|"          But Damon (such the husband's name), 'tis clear,"|FALSE
5300|"          Thought otherwise, as we shall make appear."|FALSE
5300|"          He merits pity, and should be excused,"|FALSE
5300|"          Since he, by bad advice, was much abused;"|FALSE
5300|"          When had he trusted to himself to guide,"|FALSE
5300|"          He'd acted wisely,'--hear and you'll decide."|FALSE
5300|"          THE Enchantress Neria flourished in those days;"|FALSE
5300|"          E'en Circe, she excelled in Satan's ways;"|FALSE
5300|"          The storms she made obedient to her will,"|FALSE
5300|"          And regulated with superior skill;"|FALSE
5300|"          In chains the destinies she kept around;"|FALSE
5300|"          The gentle zephyrs were her sages found;"|FALSE
5300|"          The winds, her lacqueys, flew with rapid course;"|FALSE
5300|"          Alert, but obstinate, with pow'rful force."|FALSE
5300|"          WITH all her art th' enchantress could not find,"|FALSE
5300|"          A charm to guard her 'gainst the urchin blind;"|FALSE
5300|"          Though she'd the pow'r to stop the star of day,"|FALSE
5300|"          She burned to gain a being formed of clay."|FALSE
5300|"          If merely a salute her wish had been,"|FALSE
5300|"          She might have had it, easily was seen;"|FALSE
5300|"          But bliss unbounded clearly was her view,"|FALSE
5300|"          And this with anxious ardour she'd pursue."|FALSE
5300|"          Though charms she had, still Damon would remain,"|FALSE
5300|"          To her who had his heart a faithful swain:"|FALSE
5300|"          In vain she sought the genial soft caress:"|FALSE
5300|"          To Neria naught but friendship he'd express."|FALSE
5300|"          Like Damon, husbands nowhere now are found,"|FALSE
5300|"          And I'm not certain, such were e'er on ground."|FALSE
5300|"          I rather fancy, hist'ry is not here,"|FALSE
5300|"          What we would wish, since truth it don't revere,"|FALSE
5300|"          I nothing in the hippogriff perceive,"|FALSE
5300|"          Or lance enchanted, but we may believe;"|FALSE
5300|"          Yet this I must confess has raised surprise,"|FALSE
5300|"          Howe'er, to pass it will perhaps suffice;"|FALSE
5300|"          I've many passed the same,--in ancient days;"|FALSE
5300|"          Men different were from us: had other ways;"|FALSE
5300|"          Unlike the present manners, we'll suppose;"|FALSE
5300|"          Or history would other facts disclose."|FALSE
5300|"          THE am'rous Neria to obtain her end,"|FALSE
5300|"          Made use of philters, and would e'en descend;"|FALSE
5300|"          To ev'ry wily look and secret art,"|FALSE
5300|"          That could to him she loved her flame impart."|FALSE
5300|"          Our swain his marriage vow to this opposed;"|FALSE
5300|"          At which th' enchantress much surprise disclosed."|FALSE
5300|"          You doubtless fancy, she exclaimed one day,"|FALSE
5300|"          That your fidelity must worth display;"|FALSE
5300|"          But I should like to know if equal care,"|FALSE
5300|"          Calista takes to act upon the square."|FALSE
5300|"          Suppose your wife had got a smart gallant,"|FALSE
5300|"          Would you refuse as much a fair to grant?"|FALSE
5300|"          And if Calista, careless of your fame,"|FALSE
5300|"          Should carry to extremes a guilty flame,"|FALSE
5300|"          Would you but half way go? I truly thought,"|FALSE
5300|"          By sturdy hymen thus you'd not be caught."|FALSE
5300|"          Domestick joys should be to cits confined;"|FALSE
5300|"          For none but such were scenes like those designed."|FALSE
5300|"          BUT as to you:--decline Love's choice pursuit!"|FALSE
5300|"          No anxious wish to taste forbidden fruit?"|FALSE
5300|"          Though such you banish from your thoughts I see,"|FALSE
5300|"          A friend thereto I fain would have you be."|FALSE
5300|"          Come make the trial: you'll Calista find,"|FALSE
5300|"          Quite new again when to her arms resigned."|FALSE
5300|"          But let me tell you, though your wife be chaste,"|FALSE
5300|"          Erastus to your mansion oft is traced."|FALSE
5300|"          AND do you think, cried Damon with an air,"|FALSE
5300|"          Erastus visits as a lover there?"|FALSE
5300|"          Too much he seems, my friend, to act a part,"|FALSE
5300|"          That proves the villain both in head and heart."|FALSE
5300|"          SAID Neria, mortified at this reply,"|FALSE
5300|"          Though he's a friend on whom you may rely,"|FALSE
5300|"          Calista beauty has; much worth the man,"|FALSE
5300|"          With smart address to execute his plan;"|FALSE
5300|"          And when we meet accomplishments so rare;"|FALSE
5300|"          Few women but will tumble in the snare."|FALSE
5300|"          THIS conversation was by Damon felt,"|FALSE
5300|"          A wife, brisk, young, and formed 'mid joys to melt;"|FALSE
5300|"          A man well versed in Cupid's wily way;"|FALSE
5300|"          No courtier bolder of the present day;"|FALSE
5300|"          Well made and handsome, with attractive mind;"|FALSE
5300|"          Wo what might happen was the husband blind?"|FALSE
5300|"          Whoever trusts implicitly to friends,"|FALSE
5300|"          Too oft will find, on shadows he depends."|FALSE
5300|"          Pray where's the devotee, who could withstand,"|FALSE
5300|"          The tempting glimpse of charms that all command;"|FALSE
5300|"          Which first invite by halves: then bolder grow,"|FALSE
5300|"          Till fascination spreads, and bosoms glow?"|FALSE
5300|"          Our Damon fancied this already done,"|FALSE
5300|"          Or, at the best, might be too soon begun:"|FALSE
5300|"          On these foundations gloomy views arose,"|FALSE
5300|"          Chimeras dire, destructive of repose."|FALSE
5300|"          TH' enchantress presently a hint received,"|FALSE
5300|"          That those suspicions much the husband grieved;"|FALSE
5300|"          And better to succeed and make him fret,"|FALSE
5300|"          She told him of a thing, 'mong witches met,"|FALSE
5300|"          'Twas metamorphose-water (such the name)"|FALSE
5300|"          With this could Damon take Erastus' frame;"|FALSE
5300|"          His gait, his look, his carriage, air and voice"|FALSE
5300|"          Thus changed, he easily could mark her choice,"|FALSE
5300|"          Each step observe:--enough, he asked no more,"|FALSE
5300|"          Erastus' shape the husband quickly bore;"|FALSE
5300|"          His easy manner, and appearance caught:"|FALSE
5300|"          With captivating smiles his wife he sought."|FALSE
5300|"          And thus addressed the fair with ev'ry grace:--"|FALSE
5300|"          How blithe that look! enchanting is your face;"|FALSE
5300|"          Your beauty's always great, I needs must say,"|FALSE
5300|"          But never more delightful than to-day."|FALSE
5300|"          CALISTA saw the flatt'ring lover's scheme;"|FALSE
5300|"          And turned to ridicule the wily theme."|FALSE
5300|"          His manner Damon changed, from gay to grave:"|FALSE
5300|"          Now sighs, then tears; but nothing could enslave;"|FALSE
5300|"          The lady, virtue firmly would maintain;"|FALSE
5300|"          At length, the husband, seeing all was vain,"|FALSE
5300|"          Proposed a bribe, and offered such a sum,"|FALSE
5300|"          Her anger dropt: the belle was overcome."|FALSE
5300|"          The price was very large, it might excuse,"|FALSE
5300|"          Though she at first was prompted to refuse;"|FALSE
5300|"          At last, howe'er her chastity gave way:"|FALSE
5300|"          To gold's allurements few will offer nay!"|FALSE
5300|"          The cash, resistance had so fully laid,"|FALSE
5300|"          Surrender would at any time be made."|FALSE
5300|"          The precious ore has universal charms,"|FALSE
5300|"          Enchains the will, or sets the world in arms!"|FALSE
5300|"          THOUGH elegant your form, and smart your dress,"|FALSE
5300|"          Your air, your language, ev'ry warmth express"|FALSE
5300|"          Yet, if a banker, or a financier,"|FALSE
5300|"          With handsome presents happen to appear,"|FALSE
5300|"          At once is blessed the wealthy paramour,"|FALSE
5300|"          While you a year may languish at the door."|FALSE
5300|"          THIS heart, inflexible, it seems, gave ground,"|FALSE
5300|"          To money's pow'rful, all-subduing sound;"|FALSE
5300|"          The rock now disappeared--and, in its stead,"|FALSE
5300|"          A lamb was found, quite easy to be led,"|FALSE
5300|"          Who, as a proof, resistance she would wave,"|FALSE
5300|"          A kiss, by way of earnest freely gave."|FALSE
5300|"          No further would the husband push the dame,"|FALSE
5300|"          Nor be himself a witness of his shame,"|FALSE
5300|"          But straight resumed his form, and to his wife,"|FALSE
5300|"          Cried, O Calista! once my soul and life"|FALSE
5300|"          Calista, whom I fondly cherished long;"|FALSE
5300|"          Calista, whose affection was so strong;"|FALSE
5300|"          Is gold more dear than hearts in union twined?"|FALSE
5300|"          To wash thy guilt, thy blood should be assigned."|FALSE
5300|"          But still I love thee, spite of evil thought;"|FALSE
5300|"          My death will pay the ills thou'st on me brought."|FALSE
5300|"          THE metamorphosis our dame surprised;"|FALSE
5300|"          To give relief her tears but just sufficed;"|FALSE
5300|"          She scarcely spoke; the husband, days remained,"|FALSE
5300|"          Reflecting on the circumstance that pained."|FALSE
5300|"          Himself a cuckold could he ever make,"|FALSE
5300|"          By mere design a liberty to take?"|FALSE
5300|"          But, horned or not? the question seemed to be,"|FALSE
5300|"          When Neria told him, if from doubts not free,"|FALSE
5300|"          Drink from the cup:--with so much art 'tis made,"|FALSE
5300|"          That, whose'er of cuckoldom 's afraid,"|FALSE
5300|"          Let him but put it to his eager lips"|FALSE
5300|"          If he's a cuckold, out the liquor slips;"|FALSE
5300|"          He naught can swallow; and the whole is thrown"|FALSE
5300|"          About his face or clothes, as oft 's been shown."|FALSE
5300|"          But should, from out his brow, no horns yet pop--"|FALSE
5300|"          He drinks the whole, nor spills a single drop."|FALSE
5300|"          THE doubt to solve, our husband took a sup,"|FALSE
5300|"          From this famed, formidably, magick cup;"|FALSE
5300|"          Nor did he any of the liquor waste:--"|FALSE
5300|"          Well, I am safe, said he, my wife is chaste,"|FALSE
5300|"          Though on myself it wholly could depend;"|FALSE
5300|"          But from it what have I to apprehend?"|FALSE
5300|"          Make room, good folks, who leafless branches wear;"|FALSE
5300|"          If you desire those honours I should share."|FALSE
5300|"          Thus Damon spoke, and to his precious wife"|FALSE
5300|"          A curious sermon preached, it seems, on life."|FALSE
5300|"          IF cuckoldom, my friends, such torments give;"|FALSE
5300|"          'Tis better far 'mong savages to live!"|FALSE
5300|"          LEST worse should happen, Damon settled spies,"|FALSE
5300|"          Who, o'er his lady watched with Argus' eyes."|FALSE
5300|"          She turned coquette; restraints the FAIR awake,"|FALSE
5300|"          And only prompt more liberties to take."|FALSE
5300|"          The silly husband secrets tried to know,"|FALSE
5300|"          And rather seemed to seek the wily foe,"|FALSE
5300|"          Which fear has often rendered fatal round,"|FALSE
5300|"          When otherwise the ill had ne'er been found."|FALSE
5300|"          FOUR times an hour his lips to sip he placed;"|FALSE
5300|"          And clearly, for a week was not disgraced."|FALSE
5300|"          Howe'er, no further went his ease of mind;"|FALSE
5300|"          Oh, fatal science! fatally designed!"|FALSE
5300|"          With fury Damon threw the cup away,"|FALSE
5300|"          And, in his rage, himself inclined to slay."|FALSE
5300|"          HIS wife he straight shut up within a tower,"|FALSE
5300|"          Where, morn and night, he showed a husband's pow'r,"|FALSE
5300|"          Reproach bestowed: while she bewailed her lot,"|FALSE
5300|"          'Twere better far, if he'd concealed the blot;"|FALSE
5300|"          For now, from mouth to mouth, and ear to ear,"|FALSE
5300|"          It echoed, and re-echoed far and near."|FALSE
5300|"          MEANWHILE Calista led a wretched life;"|FALSE
5300|"          No gold nor jewels Damon left his wife,"|FALSE
5300|"          Which made the jailer faithful, since 'twere vain"|FALSE
5300|"          To hope, unbribed, this Cerberus to gain."|FALSE
5300|"          AT length, the wife a lucky moment sought,"|FALSE
5300|"          When Damon seemed by soft caresses caught."|FALSE
5300|"          Said she, I've guilty been, I freely own;"|FALSE
5300|"          But though my crime is great, I'm not alone;"|FALSE
5300|"          Alas! how few escape from like mishap;"|FALSE
5300|"          'Mong Hymen's band so common is the trap;"|FALSE
5300|"          And though at you the immaculate may smile,"|FALSE
5300|"          What use to fret and all the sex revile?"|FALSE
5300|"          WELL I'll console myself, and pardon you,"|FALSE
5300|"          Cried Damon, when sufficient I can view,"|FALSE
5300|"          Of ornamented foreheads, just like mine,"|FALSE
5300|"          To form among themselves a royal line;"|FALSE
5300|"          'Tis only to employ the magick cup,"|FALSE
5300|"          From which I learned your secrets by a sup."|FALSE
5300|"          HIS plan to execute, the husband went,"|FALSE
5300|"          And ev'ry passenger was thither sent,"|FALSE
5300|"          Where Damon entertained, with sumptuous fare;"|FALSE
5300|"          And, at the end, proposed the magick snare:"|FALSE
5300|"          Said he, my wife played truant to my bed;"|FALSE
5300|"          Wish you to know if your's be e'er misled?"|FALSE
5300|"          'Tis right how things go on at home to trace,"|FALSE
5300|"          And if upon the cup your lips you place,"|FALSE
5300|"          In case your wife be chaste, there'll naught go wrong;"|FALSE
5300|"          But, if to Vulcan's troop you should belong,"|FALSE
5300|"          And prove an antlered brother, you will spill"|FALSE
5300|"          The liquor ev'ry way, in spite of skill."|FALSE
5300|"          TO all the men, that Damon could collect,"|FALSE
5300|"          The cup he offered, and they tried th' effect;"|FALSE
5300|"          But few escaped, at which they laughed or cried,"|FALSE
5300|"          As feelings led, or cuckoldom they spied,"|FALSE
5300|"          Whose surly countenance the wags believed,"|FALSE
5300|"          In many houses near, might be perceived."|FALSE
5300|"          ALREADY Damon had sufficient found,"|FALSE
5300|"          To form a regiment and march around;"|FALSE
5300|"          At times they threatened governors to hang,"|FALSE
