5300|"                        THE AUTHOR'S PREFACE"|FALSE
5300|"                 TO HIS SECOND BOOK OF THESE TALES"|FALSE
5300|"These are the last works of this style that  will come from the pen of"|FALSE
5300|"the Author, and  consequently this is the last opportunity he has of"|FALSE
5300|"vindicating the boldness and privilege which he has assumed.  We make no"|FALSE
5300|"mention of villainous rhymes, of lines that run into the next, of two"|FALSE
5300|"vowels without elision, nor, in general, of such  kinds of carelessness"|FALSE
5300|"as he would not allow himself in another style of poetry, but which"|FALSE
5300|"are part and parcel, so to say, of this style.  Too anxious a care"|FALSE
5300|"in avoiding such would force a tale-writer into a labyrinth of shifts,"|FALSE
5300|"into narratives as dull as they are grand, into straits that are utterly"|FALSE
5300|"useless, and would make him disregard the pleasure of the heart in order"|FALSE
5300|"to labour for the gratification of the ear.  We must leave studied"|FALSE
5300|"narrative for lofty subjects, and not compose an epic poem of the"|FALSE
5300|"Adventures of Renaud d'Ast.  Suppose the Author, who has put these tales"|FALSE
5300|"into rhyme, had brought to bear on them all the care and preciseness"|FALSE
5300|"required of him; not only would this care be observed, especially as it"|FALSE
5300|"is unnecessary, but it would also transgress the precept lain down by"|FALSE
5300|"Ouintilian, still the Author would not have attained the main object,"|FALSE
5300|"which is to interest the reader, to charm him, to rivet his attention"|FALSE
5300|"in spite of himself,--in a word, to please him.  As everybody knows, the"|FALSE
5300|"secret of pleasing the reader is not always based on regulation, nor even"|FALSE
5300|"on symmetry; there is need of smartness and tastefulness, if we would"|FALSE
5300|"strike home.  How many of those perfect types of beauty do we see which"|FALSE
5300|"never strike home, and of which nobody feels enamoured!  We do not wish"|FALSE
5300|"to rob Modern Authors of the praise that is due to them.  Nicely turned"|FALSE
5300|"lines, fine language, accuracy, elegance of rhyme are accomplishments in"|FALSE
5300|"a poet. However that may be, let us consider  of our own epigrams wherein"|FALSE
5300|"all these qualities are combined, perhaps we shall find in them far less"|FALSE
5300|"point, nay, I would venture to add, far less  charm than in those of"|FALSE
5300|"Marot or Saint-Gelais, although almost all the works of the latter poets"|FALSE
5300|"are full of the same faults as are attributed to us.  We will be told"|FALSE
5300|"that these were not faults in their day, whereas they are very great"|FALSE
5300|"faults in ours.  To this we answer by a similar kind of argument, by"|FALSE
5300|"saying, as we have already said, that these would undoubtedly be faults"|FALSE
5300|"in another style of  poetry, but not in this.  The late M. de Voiture is"|FALSE
5300|"a proof in point. We need only read the works in which he brings to life"|FALSE
5300|"again the character of Marot.  For our Author does not lay claim to"|FALSE
5300|"praise for himself, nor to rounds of applause from the public for having"|FALSE
5300|"put a few tales into rhyme.  Without doubt he has entered on quite a new"|FALSE
5300|"path, and has pursued it to the utmost of his power, choosing now one"|FALSE
5300|"road, now another, and always treading with surer step when he has"|FALSE
5300|"followed the manner of our old poets \"quorum in hae re imitari"|FALSE
5300|"negligentiam exoptat potius quam istorum diligentiam.\""|FALSE
5300|"But while saying that we wished to waive this question, we have"|FALSE
5300|"unconsciously involved ourselves in its discussion.  Perhaps this has not"|FALSE
5300|"been without advantage; for there is nothing that resembles faults more"|FALSE
5300|"than these licenses.  Let us now consider the liberty which the Author"|FALSE
5300|"has assumed in cutting into the property of others as well as  his own,"|FALSE
5300|"without making exception even to the  best known stories, none of which"|FALSE
5300|"he scruples to tamper with.  He curtails, enlarges, and alters incidents"|FALSE
5300|"and details, at times the main issue and the sequel; in short, the story"|FALSE
5300|"is no longer the same;  it is, in point of fact, quite a new tale; its"|FALSE
5300|"original author would find it no small difficulty to recognise in it his"|FALSE
5300|"own work. \"Non sic decet contaminari  fabulas,\" Critics will say.  Why"|FALSE
5300|"should they not?  They twitted Terence in just the same way; but Terence"|FALSE
5300|"sneered at them, and claimed a right to treat the matter as he did.  He"|FALSE
5300|"has mingled his own ideas with the subjects he drew from Menander, just"|FALSE
5300|"as Sophocles and Euripides mingled theirs with the subjects they drew"|FALSE
5300|"from former writers, sparing neither history nor romance, where \"decorum\""|FALSE
5300|"and the rules of the Drama were at issue.  Shall this privilege cease"|FALSE
5300|"with respect to fictitious stories?  Must we in future have more"|FALSE
5300|"scrupulous or religious regard, if we may be allowed the expression,"|FALSE
5300|"for falsehood than the Ancients had for truth?  What people call a good"|FALSE
5300|"tale never passes from hand to hand without receiving some fresh touch"|FALSE
5300|"of embellishment.  How comes it then, we may be asked, that in many"|FALSE
5300|"passages the Author curtails instead of enlarging on the original?"|FALSE
5300|"On that point we are agreed:  the Author does so in order to avoid"|FALSE
5300|"lengthiness and ambiguity,--two faults which are inadmissible in such"|FALSE
5300|"matters, especially the latter.  For if lucidity is to be commended in"|FALSE
5300|"all literary works, we may say that it is especially necessary in"|FALSE
5300|"narratives, where one thing is, as a rule, the sequel and the result of"|FALSE
5300|"another; where the less important sometimes lays the basis of the more"|FALSE
5300|"important; so that, once the thread becomes broken, the reader cannot"|FALSE
5300|"gather it up again.  Besides, as narratives in verse are very awkward,"|FALSE
5300|"the author must clog himself with details as little as possible; by means"|FALSE
5300|"of this you relieve not only yourself, but also the reader, for whom an"|FALSE
5300|"author should not fail to prepare pleasure unalloyed.  Whenever the"|FALSE
5300|"Author has altered a few particulars and even a few catastrophes, he has"|FALSE
5300|"been forced to do so by the cause of that catastrophe and the urgency of"|FALSE
5300|"giving it a happy termination. He has fancied that in tales of this kind"|FALSE
5300|"everyone ought to be satisfied with the end: it pleases the reader at"|FALSE
5300|"any rate, if the author has not given the characters too distasteful"|FALSE
5300|"a rendering.  But he must not go so far as that, if possible, nor make"|FALSE
5300|"the reader laugh and cry in the same tale.  This medley shocks Horace"|FALSE
5300|"above all things; his wish is not that our works should border on the"|FALSE
5300|"grotesque, and that we should draw a picture half woman half fish.  These"|FALSE
5300|"are the general motives the Author has had in view.  We might still quote"|FALSE
5300|"special motives and vindicate each point; but we must needs leave"|FALSE
5300|"something to the capacity and leniency of our readers.  They will be"|FALSE
5300|"satisfied, then, with the motives we have mentioned.  We would have"|FALSE
5300|"stated them more clearly and have set more by them, had the general"|FALSE
5300|"compass of a Preface so allowed."|FALSE
5300|"                    FRIAR PHILIP'S GEESE"|FALSE
5300|"          IF these gay tales give pleasure to the FAIR,"|FALSE
