5300|"          An age, when those, for solitude designed,"|FALSE
5300|"          Should be to scenes of seriousness confined,"|FALSE
5300|"          Nor joys of youth, nor soft ideas praised"|FALSE
5300|"          The flame soon spreads when Cupid's torch is raised."|FALSE
5300|"          AT length, when twenty summers time had run,"|FALSE
5300|"          The father to the city brought his son;"|FALSE
5300|"          With years weighed down, the hermit scarcely knew"|FALSE
5300|"          His daily course of duty to pursue;"|FALSE
5300|"          And when Death's venomed shaft should on him fall;"|FALSE
5300|"          On whom could then his boy for succour call?"|FALSE
5300|"          How life support, unknowing and unknown?"|FALSE
5300|"          Wolves, foxes, bears, ne'er charity have shown;"|FALSE
5300|"          And all the sire could give his darling care,"|FALSE
5300|"          A staff and wallet, he was well aware"|FALSE
5300|"          Fine patrimony, truly, for a child!"|FALSE
5300|"          To which his mind was no way reconciled."|FALSE
5300|"          Bread few, 'twas clear, the hermit would deny,"|FALSE
5300|"          And rich he might have been you may rely;"|FALSE
5300|"          When he drew near, the children quickly cried"|FALSE
5300|"          Here's father Philip--haste, the alms provide;"|FALSE
5300|"          And many pious men his friends were found,"|FALSE
5300|"          But not one female devotee around:"|FALSE
5300|"          None would he hear; the FAIR he always fled"|FALSE
5300|"          Their smiles and wiles the friar kept in dread."|FALSE
5300|"          OUR hermit, when he thought his darling youth;"|FALSE
5300|"          Well fixed in duty and religious truth,"|FALSE
5300|"          Conveyed him 'mong his pious friends, to learn"|FALSE
5300|"          How food to beg, and other ways discern."|FALSE
5300|"          In tears he viewed his son the forest quit,"|FALSE
5300|"          And fain would have him for the world unfit."|FALSE
5300|"          THE city's palaces and lofty spires,"|FALSE
5300|"          Our rustick's bosom filled with new desires."|FALSE
5300|"          The prince's residence great splendour showed,"|FALSE
5300|"          And lively pleasure on the youth bestowed."|FALSE
5300|"          What's here? said he; The court, his friends replied:--"|FALSE
5300|"          What there?--The mansions where the great reside:--"|FALSE
5300|"          And these?--Fine statues, noble works of art:"|FALSE
5300|"          All gave delight and gratitude his heart."|FALSE
5300|"          But when the beauteous FAIR first caught his view,"|FALSE
5300|"          To ev'ry other sight he bade adieu;"|FALSE
5300|"          The palace, court, or mansions he admired,"|FALSE
5300|"          No longer proved the objects he desired;"|FALSE
5300|"          Another cause of admiration rose,"|FALSE
5300|"          His breast pervaded, and disturbed repose."|FALSE
5300|"          What's this, he cried, so elegantly neat?"|FALSE
5300|"          O tell me, father; make my joy complete!"|FALSE
5300|"          WHAT gave the son such exquisite delight,"|FALSE
5300|"          The parent filled with agonizing fright."|FALSE
5300|"          To answer, howsoe'er he'd no excuse,"|FALSE
5300|"          So told the youth--a bird they call a goose."|FALSE
5300|"          O BEAUTEOUS bird, exclaimed th' enraptured boy,"|FALSE
5300|"          Sing, sound thy voice, 'twill fill my soul with joy;"|FALSE
5300|"          To thee I'd anxiously be better known;"|FALSE
5300|"          O father, let me have one for my own!"|FALSE
5300|"          A thousand times I fondly ask the boon;"|FALSE
5300|"          Let's take it to the woods: 'tis not too soon;"|FALSE
5300|"          Young as it is, I'll feed it morn and night,"|FALSE
5300|"          And always make it my supreme delight."|FALSE
5300|"                        RICHARD MINUTOLO"|FALSE
5300|"          IN ev'ry age, at Naples, we are told,"|FALSE
5300|"          Intrigue and gallantry reign uncontrolled;"|FALSE
5300|"          With beauteous objects in abundance blessed."|FALSE
5300|"          No country round so many has possessed;"|FALSE
5300|"          Such fascinating charms the FAIR disclose,"|FALSE
5300|"          That irresistibly soft passion flows."|FALSE
5300|"          'MONG these a belle, enchanting to behold,"|FALSE
5300|"          Was loved by one, of birth and store of gold;"|FALSE
5300|"          Minutolo (and Richard) was his name,"|FALSE
5300|"          In Cupid's train a youth of brilliant fame:"|FALSE
5300|"          'Tween Rome and Paris none was more gallant,"|FALSE
5300|"          And num'rous hearts were for him known to pant."|FALSE
5300|"          CATELLA (thus was called our lady fair,)"|FALSE
5300|"          So long, howe'er, resisted Richard's snare,"|FALSE
5300|"          That prayers, and vows, and promises were vain;"|FALSE
5300|"          A favour Minutolo could not gain."|FALSE
5300|"          At length, our hero weary, coldness showed,"|FALSE
5300|"          And dropt attendance, since no kindness flowed;"|FALSE
5300|"          Pretended to be cured:--another sought,"|FALSE
5300|"          And feigned her charms his tender heart had caught:"|FALSE
5300|"          Catella laughed, but jealousy was nigh;"|FALSE
5300|"          'Twas for her friend that now He heaved the sigh."|FALSE
5300|"          THESE dames together met, and Richard too,"|FALSE
5300|"          The gay gallant a glowing picture drew,"|FALSE
5300|"          Of certain husbands, lovers, prudes, and wives;"|FALSE
5300|"          Who led in secret most lascivious lives."|FALSE
5300|"          Though none he named, Catella was amazed;"|FALSE
5300|"          His hints suspicions of her husband raised;"|FALSE
5300|"          And such her agitation and affright,"|FALSE
5300|"          That, anxious to procure more certain light,"|FALSE
5300|"          In haste she took Minutolo aside,"|FALSE
5300|"          And begged the names he would not from her hide,"|FALSE
5300|"          With all particulars, from first to last:--"|FALSE
5300|"          Her ardent wish to know whate'er had passed."|FALSE
5300|"          SO long your reign, said Richard, o'er my mind,"|FALSE
5300|"          Deny I could not, howsoe'er inclined;"|FALSE
5300|"          With Mrs. Simon often is your spouse;"|FALSE
5300|"          Her character no doubt your spleen will rouse;"|FALSE
5300|"          I've no design, observe to give offence,"|FALSE
5300|"          But, when I see your int'rest in suspense,"|FALSE
5300|"          I cannot silent keep; though, were I still"|FALSE
5300|"          A slave, devoted wholly to your will,"|FALSE
5300|"          As late I moved, I would not drop a word"|FALSE
5300|"          Mistrust of lovers may not be absurd;"|FALSE
5300|"          Besides, you'd fancy other motives led"|FALSE
5300|"          To tell you of your husband what was said;"|FALSE
5300|"          But heav'n be praised, of you I nothing want;"|FALSE
5300|"          My object's plain--no more the fond gallant."|FALSE
5300|"          I'VE lately certain information had,"|FALSE
5300|"          Your spouse (I scarcely thought the man so bad,)"|FALSE
5300|"          Has with the lady an appointment made;"|FALSE
5300|"          At Jack's nice bagnio he will meet the jade."|FALSE
5300|"          NOW clearly Jack's not rich, and there's no doubt;"|FALSE
5300|"          A hundred ducats give, and--ALL will out;"|FALSE
5300|"          Let him but have a handsome sum in view,"|FALSE
5300|"          And any thing you wish, be sure he'll do;"|FALSE
5300|"          You then can manage ev'ry way so well,"|FALSE
5300|"          That, at the place assigned to meet his belle,"|FALSE
5300|"          You'll take this truant husband by surprise;--"|FALSE
5300|"          Permit me in this nice affair to advise."|FALSE
5300|"          THE lady has agreed, you will remark,"|FALSE
5300|"          That in a room where ev'ry part is dark,"|FALSE
5300|"          (Perhaps to 'scape the keeper's prying sight,"|FALSE
5300|"          Or shame directs exclusion of the light,)"|FALSE
5300|"          She will receive your gay inconstant spouse;"|FALSE
5300|"          Now, take her place; the case deceit allows;"|FALSE
5300|"          Make Jack your friend; nor haggle at the price;"|FALSE
5300|"          A hundred ducats give, is my advice;"|FALSE
5300|"          He'll place you in the room where darkness reigns;"|FALSE
5300|"          Think not too fast, nor suffer heavy chains;"|FALSE
5300|"          Do what you wish, and utter not a word;"|FALSE
5300|"          To speak, assuredly would be absurd;"|FALSE
