5300|"          Had no effect: still circular 'twould go."|FALSE
5300|"          The more he tried, the ringlet less inclined"|FALSE
5300|"          To drop the curvature so closely twined."|FALSE
5300|"          How's this? said Satan, never have I seen"|FALSE
5300|"          Such stubborn stuff wherever I have been;"|FALSE
5300|"          The shades below no demon can produce,"|FALSE
5300|"          That could divine what here would prove of use:"|FALSE
5300|"          'Twould puzzle hell to break the curling spring,"|FALSE
5300|"          And make a line direct of such a thing."|FALSE
5300|"          ONE morn the devil to the other went:"|FALSE
5300|"          Said he, to give thee up I'll be content;"|FALSE
5300|"          If solely thou wilt openly declare"|FALSE
5300|"          What 'tis I hold, for truly I despair;"|FALSE
5300|"          I'm victus I confess, and can't succeed:"|FALSE
5300|"          No doubt the thing's impossible decreed."|FALSE
5300|"          FRIEND Satan, said the lover, you are wrong;"|FALSE
5300|"          Despondency should not to you belong,"|FALSE
5300|"          At least so soon:--what you desire to know"|FALSE
5300|"          Is not the only one that's found to grow;"|FALSE
5300|"          Still many more companions it has got,"|FALSE
5300|"          And others could be taken from the spot."|FALSE
5300|"                         THE PICTURE"|FALSE
5300|"          SOLICITED I've been to give a tale,"|FALSE
5300|"          In which (though true, decorum must prevail),"|FALSE
5300|"          The subject from a picture shall arise,"|FALSE
5300|"          That by a curtain's kept from vulgar eyes."|FALSE
5300|"          My brain must furnish various features new:"|FALSE
5300|"          What's delicate and smart produce to view;"|FALSE
5300|"          By this expressed, and not by t'other said:"|FALSE
5300|"          And all so clear, most easy to be read,"|FALSE
5300|"          By ev'ry fool, without the aid of notes,"|FALSE
5300|"          That idiot's bad indeed who never quotes."|FALSE
5300|"          CATULLUS tells us, ev'ry matron sage"|FALSE
5300|"          Will peep most willingly (whate'er her age),"|FALSE
5300|"          At that gigantick gift, which Juno made,"|FALSE
5300|"          To Venus' fruit, in gardens oft displayed."|FALSE
5300|"          If any belle recede, and shun the sight,"|FALSE
5300|"          Dissimulation she supposes right."|FALSE
5300|"          THIS principle allowed, why scruples make?"|FALSE
5300|"          Why, less than eyes, should ears a license take?"|FALSE
5300|"          But since 'tis so resolved I'll do my best,"|FALSE
5300|"          And naught in open terms shall be expressed:"|FALSE
5300|"          A veil shall over ev'ry charm be cast,"|FALSE
5300|"          Of gauze indeed, and this from first to last,"|FALSE
5300|"          So nicely done, that howsoever tost,"|FALSE
5300|"          To none I trust will any thing be lost."|FALSE
5300|"          Who nicely thinks, and speaks with graceful ease;"|FALSE
5300|"          Can current make just whatsoe'er he please;"|FALSE
5300|"          For all will pass, as I have often known:"|FALSE
5300|"          The word well chosen, pardon soon is shown,"|FALSE
5300|"          The sex o'erlook the thing no more the same,"|FALSE
5300|"          The thought remains, but 'tis without a name;"|FALSE
5300|"          No blush is raised; no difficulty found;"|FALSE
5300|"          Yet ev'ry body understands around."|FALSE
5300|"          AT present, much I need this useful art:"|FALSE
5300|"          Why? you will ask; because, when I impart"|FALSE
5300|"          Such wondrous circumstances, ev'ry belle,"|FALSE
5300|"          Without reserve, will con them over well."|FALSE
5300|"          To this I answer: female ears are chaste,"|FALSE
5300|"          Though roguish are their eyes, as well as taste."|FALSE
5300|"          BE that as 'twill, I certainly should like,"|FALSE
5300|"          With freedom to explain, by terms oblique,"|FALSE
5300|"          To belles, how this was broken:--that was down:"|FALSE
5300|"          Assist me pray, ye NINE of high renown;"|FALSE
5300|"          But you are maids, and strangers, we agree,"|FALSE
5300|"          To LOVE'S soft scenes, not knowing A from B."|FALSE
5300|"          Remain then, Muses, never stir an inch,"|FALSE
5300|"          But beg the god of verse, when at a pinch,"|FALSE
5300|"          To help me out and kind assistance lend,"|FALSE
5300|"          To choose expressions which will not offend,"|FALSE
5300|"          Lest I some silly things should chance to say,"|FALSE
5300|"          That might displeasure raise, and spoil my lay."|FALSE
5300|"          Enough, howe'er, we've on the subject said:"|FALSE
5300|"          'Tis time we t'wards the painting should be led,"|FALSE
5300|"          Which an adventure you will find contains,"|FALSE
5300|"          That happened once in Cupid's famed domains."|FALSE
5300|"          IN former days, just by Cythera town"|FALSE
5300|"          A monastery was, of some renown,"|FALSE
5300|"          With nuns the queens of beauty filled the place,"|FALSE
5300|"          And gay gallants you easily might trace."|FALSE
5300|"          The courtier, citizen, and parson too,"|FALSE
5300|"          The doctor and the bachelor you'd view,"|FALSE
5300|"          With eager steps:--all visits thither made;"|FALSE
5300|"          And 'mong the latter, one (a pleasing blade)"|FALSE
5300|"          Had free access: was thought a prudent friend,"|FALSE
5300|"          Who might to sisters many comforts lend;"|FALSE
5300|"          Was always closely shaved and nicely dressed;"|FALSE
5300|"          And ev'ry thing he said was well expressed;"|FALSE
5300|"          The breath of scandal, howsoever pat,"|FALSE
5300|"          Ne'er lighted on his neat cravat nor hat."|FALSE
5300|"          TWO nuns alternatively, from the youth;"|FALSE
5300|"          Experienced many services, in truth;"|FALSE
5300|"          The one had recently a novice been;"|FALSE
5300|"          Few months had passed since she complete was seen;"|FALSE
5300|"          The other still the dress of novice wore;"|FALSE
5300|"          The youngest's age was seventeen years, not more"|FALSE
5300|"          Time doubtless very proper (to be plain)"|FALSE
5300|"          Love's wily thesis fully to sustain:"|FALSE
5300|"          The bachelor so well the fair had taught,"|FALSE
5300|"          And they so earnestly the science sought,"|FALSE
5300|"          That by experience both the art had learned,"|FALSE
5300|"          And ev'ry thing most perfectly discerned."|FALSE
5300|"          THESE sisters eagerly had made one day"|FALSE
5300|"          An assignation with the lover gay;"|FALSE
5300|"          To have the entertainment quite complete,"|FALSE
5300|"          They'd Bacchus, Ceres too, who Venus greet:"|FALSE
5300|"          With perfect neatness all the meats were served,"|FALSE
5300|"          And naught from grace and elegancy swerved;"|FALSE
5300|"          The wines, the custards, jellies, creams, and ice:"|FALSE
5300|"          The decorations, ev'ry thing was nice;"|FALSE
5300|"          What pleasing objects and delights were viewed!"|FALSE
5300|"          The room with sweetest flow'rs fair Flora strewed;"|FALSE
5300|"          A sort of garden o'er the linen traced"|FALSE
5300|"          Here lakes of love:--there names entwined were placed;"|FALSE
5300|"          Magnificence like this the nuns admired,"|FALSE
5300|"          And such amusements ardently desired."|FALSE
5300|"          Their beauty too incited to be free;"|FALSE
5300|"          A thousand matters filled their souls with glee;"|FALSE
5300|"          In height the belles were pretty much the same"|FALSE
5300|"          Like alabaster fair; of perfect frame;"|FALSE
5300|"          In num'rous corners Cupid nestling lay:"|FALSE
5300|"          Beneath a stomacher he'd slyly play,"|FALSE
5300|"          A veil or scapulary, this or that,"|FALSE
5300|"          Where least the eye of day perceived he sat,"|FALSE
5300|"          Unless a lover called to mystick bow'rs,"|FALSE
5300|"          Where he might hearts entwine with chains of flow'rs;"|FALSE
5300|"          A thousand times a day the urchin flew,"|FALSE
5300|"          With open arms the sisters to pursue;"|FALSE
5300|"          Their charms were such in ev'ry air and look,"|FALSE
5300|"          Both (one by one) he for his mother took."|FALSE
5300|"          WITH anxious looks, the ladies thus prepared,"|FALSE
5300|"          Expected him who all their kindness shared;"|FALSE
5300|"          Now they bestowed abuse; next fondly praised:"|FALSE
5300|"          Then of his conduct dark suspicions raised,"|FALSE
5300|"          Conceived, a new amour him kept away:"|FALSE
5300|"          What can it be, said one, that makes him stay?"|FALSE
5300|"          Of honour an affair.--love--sickness--what?"|FALSE
5300|"          Said t'other whether it be this or that,"|FALSE
5300|"          If here again his face he ever show,"|FALSE
5300|"          A pretty trick in turn we'll let him know."|FALSE
5300|"          WHILE thus the couple sought their plot to frame,"|FALSE
5300|"          A convent porter with a burden came,"|FALSE
5300|"          For her who kept the stores of ev'ry kind,"|FALSE
5300|"          Depositary of the whole designed."|FALSE
5300|"          'Twas merely a pretence, as I am told:"|FALSE
5300|"          The things were not required for young or old;"|FALSE
5300|"          But she much appetite had got in truth,"|FALSE
5300|"          Which made her have recourse to such a youth,"|FALSE
5300|"          Who was regarded, in repasts like these,"|FALSE
5300|"          A first rate cook that all prepared at ease."|FALSE
5300|"          THIS awkward, heavy lout mistook the cell;"|FALSE
5300|"          By chance upon our ladies' room he fell,"|FALSE
5300|"          And knocked with weighty hands: they ope'd the door."|FALSE
5300|"          And gave abuse, but soon their anger o'er,"|FALSE
5300|"          The nuns conceived a treasure they had found,"|FALSE
5300|"          And, laughing heartily, no longer frowned,"|FALSE
5300|"          But both exclaimed at once: let's take this fool;"|FALSE
5300|"          Of him we easily can make a tool;"|FALSE
5300|"          As well as t'other, don't you think he'll do?"|FALSE
5300|"          The eldest added:--let's our whim pursue;"|FALSE
5300|"          'Tis well determined;--What were we to get,"|FALSE
5300|"          That here we waited, and are waiting yet?"|FALSE
5300|"          Fine words and phrases; nothing of the kind;"|FALSE
5300|"          This wight 's as good, for what we have a mind,"|FALSE
5300|"          As any bachelor or doctor wise"|FALSE
5300|"          At all events, for present, he'll suffice."|FALSE
5300|"          SHE rightly judged; his height, form, simple air,"|FALSE
5300|"          And ev'ry act, so clearly void of care,"|FALSE
5300|"          Raised expectation; this was AEsop's man,"|FALSE
5300|"          He never thought: 'twas all without a plan;"|FALSE
5300|"          Both ate and drank, and, had he been at will,"|FALSE
5300|"          Would matters far have pushed, though void of skill."|FALSE
5300|"          FAMILIAR grown, the fellow ready seemed,"|FALSE
5300|"          To execute whate'er was proper deemed;"|FALSE
5300|"          To serve the convent he was porter made,"|FALSE
5300|"          And in their wishes nuns of course obeyed."|FALSE
5300|"          'TIS here begins the subject we've in view,"|FALSE
5300|"          The scene that faithfully our painter drew;"|FALSE
5300|"          Apollo, give me aid, assistance lend,"|FALSE
5300|"          Enable me, I pray, to comprehend,"|FALSE
5300|"          Why this mean stupid rustick sat at ease,"|FALSE
5300|"          And left the sisters (Claudia, formed to please,"|FALSE
5300|"          And lovely fair Theresa) all the care?"|FALSE
5300|"          Had he not better done to give a chair?"|FALSE
5300|"          I THINK I hear the god of verse reply:"|FALSE
5300|"          Not quite so fast my friend, you may rely,"|FALSE
5300|"          These matters never can the probe endure;"|FALSE
5300|"          I understand you; Cupid, to be sure,"|FALSE
5300|"          Is doubtless found a very roguish boy,"|FALSE
5300|"          Who, though he please at times, will oft annoy;"|FALSE
5300|"          I'm wrong a wicked whelp like this to take,"|FALSE
5300|"          And, master of the ceremonies make."|FALSE
5300|"          NO sooner in a house the urchin gets,"|FALSE
5300|"          But rules and laws he at defiance sets;"|FALSE
5300|"          The place of reason whim at once assumes,"|FALSE
5300|"          Breaks ev'ry obstacle, frets, rages, fumes."|FALSE
5300|"          With scenes like these will Cupid oft surprise,"|FALSE
5300|"          And frantick passion sparkle in his eyes."|FALSE
5300|"          SOON on the floor was seen this boorish wight;"|FALSE
5300|"          For, whether that the chair was rather slight,"|FALSE
5300|"          Or that the composition of the clown"|FALSE
5300|"          Was not, like that of geese, of softest down,"|FALSE
5300|"          Or that Theresa, by her gay discourse,"|FALSE
5300|"          Had penetrated to the mystick source,"|FALSE
5300|"          The am'rous pulpit suddenly gave way,"|FALSE
5300|"          And on the ground the rustick quickly lay."|FALSE
5300|"          The first attempt had clearly bad success,"|FALSE
5300|"          And fair Theresa suffered you may guess."|FALSE
5300|"          YE censors keep from hence your eyes prophane;"|FALSE
5300|"          See, honest hearts, how Claudia tried amain,"|FALSE
5300|"          To take advantage of the dire mishap,"|FALSE
5300|"          And all she could, with eagerness entrap;"|FALSE
5300|"          For in the fall Theresa lost her hold;"|FALSE
5300|"          The other pushed her:--further off she rolled;"|FALSE
5300|"          And then, what she had quitted Claudia seized;"|FALSE
5300|"          Theresa, like a demon quite displeased,"|FALSE
5300|"          Endeavoured to recover what she'd lost:--"|FALSE
5300|"          Again to take her seat, but she was crossed."|FALSE
5300|"          The sister in possession ne'er inclined"|FALSE
5300|"          To cede a post so pleasant to her mind;"|FALSE
5300|"          Theresa raised her hand to give a stroke;"|FALSE
5300|"          And what of that?--if any thing provoke"|FALSE
5300|"          When thus engaged, unheeded it remains"|FALSE
5300|"          Small ills are soon forgot where pleasure reigns."|FALSE
5300|"          IN spite of rage apparent in the face;"|FALSE
5300|"          Of her who in the scuffle lost her place,"|FALSE
5300|"          The other followed up the road she took;"|FALSE
5300|"          His course the rustick also ne'er forsook."|FALSE
5300|"          Theresa scolded; anger marked her eyes;"|FALSE
5300|"          In Venus' games contentions oft arise;"|FALSE
5300|"          Their violence no parallel has seen:--"|FALSE
5300|"          In proof, remember Menelaus' queen."|FALSE
5300|"          Though here to take a part Bellona 's found,"|FALSE
5300|"          Of cuirasses I see but few around;"|FALSE
5300|"          When Venus closes with the god of Thrace,"|FALSE
5300|"          Her armour then appears with ev'ry grace."|FALSE
5300|"          The FAIR will understand: enough is said;"|FALSE
5300|"          When beauty's goddess is to combat led,"|FALSE
5300|"          Her body-cuirass shows superior charms;"|FALSE
5300|"          The Cyclops rarely forge such pleasing arms."|FALSE
5300|"          Had Vulcan graven on Achilles' shield"|FALSE
5300|"          The picture we've described, more praise 'twould yield."|FALSE
5300|"          THE nun's adventure I in verse have told,"|FALSE
5300|"          But not in colours, like the action, bold;"|FALSE
5300|"          And as the story in the picture fails,"|FALSE
5300|"          The latter seems to lose in my details."|FALSE
5300|"          The pen and brush express not quite the same;"|FALSE
5300|"          Eyes are not ears, however we may aim."|FALSE
5300|"          ENTANGLED in the net, I long have left"|FALSE
5300|"          The fair Theresa, of her throne bereft;"|FALSE
5300|"          Howe'er, this sister had her turn we find,"|FALSE
5300|"          So much to please, the porter was inclined,"|FALSE
5300|"          That both were satisfied, and felt content;"|FALSE
5300|"          Here ends our tale, and truly I lament,"|FALSE
5300|"          That not a word about the feast is said,"|FALSE
5300|"          Though I've no doubt, they freely drank and fed;"|FALSE
5300|"          And this for reasons easily conceived:"|FALSE
5300|"          The interlude gave rest that much relieved."|FALSE
5300|"          In fine, 'twas well throughout, except, in truth,"|FALSE
5300|"          The hour of meeting settled with the youth,"|FALSE
5300|"          Which much embarrasses I will avow,"|FALSE
5300|"          For if he never came and made his bow,"|FALSE
5300|"          The sisters had the means, when they might please,"|FALSE
5300|"          Completely to console themselves at ease;"|FALSE
5300|"          And if the spark appeared, the belles could hide"|FALSE
5300|"          Both clown and chair, or any thing beside"|FALSE
5300|"          The lover what he wanted soon possessed,"|FALSE
5300|"          And was as usual treated with the best."|FALSE
5300|"                       THE PACK-SADDLE"|FALSE
5300|"          A FAMOUS painter, jealous of his wife;"|FALSE
5300|"          Whose charms he valued more than fame or life,"|FALSE
5300|"          When going on a journey used his art,"|FALSE
5300|"          To paint an ASS upon a certain part,"|FALSE
5300|"          (Umbilical, 'tis said) and like a seal:"|FALSE
5300|"          Impressive token, nothing thence to steal."|FALSE
5300|"          A BROTHER brush, enamoured of the dame;"|FALSE
5300|"          Now took advantage, and declared his flame:"|FALSE
5300|"          The Ass effaced, but God knows how 'twas done;"|FALSE
5300|"          Another soon howe'er he had begun,"|FALSE
5300|"          And finished well, upon the very spot;"|FALSE
5300|"          In painting, few more praises ever got;"|FALSE
5300|"          But want of recollection made him place"|FALSE
5300|"          A saddle, where before he none could trace."|FALSE
5300|"          THE husband, when returned, desired to look"|FALSE
5300|"          At what he drew, when leave he lately took."|FALSE
5300|"          Yes, see my dear, the wily wife replied,"|FALSE
5300|"          The Ass is witness, faithful I abide."|FALSE
5300|"          Zounds! said the painter, when he got a sight,--"|FALSE
5300|"          What!--you'd persuade me ev'ry thing is right?"|FALSE
5300|"          I wish the witness you display so well,"|FALSE
5300|"          And him who saddled it, were both in Hell."|FALSE
5300|"              THE EAR-MAKER AND THE MOULD-MENDER"|FALSE
5300|"          WHEN William went from home (a trader styled):"|FALSE
5300|"          Six months his better half he left with child,"|FALSE
5300|"          A simple, comely, modest, youthful dame,"|FALSE
5300|"          Whose name was Alice; from Champaign she came."|FALSE
5300|"          Her neighbour Andrew visits now would pay;"|FALSE
5300|"          With what intention, needless 'tis to say:"|FALSE
5300|"          A master who but rarely spread his net,"|FALSE
5300|"          But, first or last, with full success he met;"|FALSE
5300|"          And cunning was the bird that 'scaped his snare;"|FALSE
5300|"          Without surrendering a feather there."|FALSE
5300|"          QUITE raw was Alice; for his purpose fit;"|FALSE
5300|"          Not overburdened with a store of wit;"|FALSE
5300|"          Of this indeed she could not be accused,"|FALSE
5300|"          And Cupid's wiles by her were never used;"|FALSE
5300|"          Poor lady, all with her was honest part,"|FALSE
5300|"          And naught she knew of stratagem or art."|FALSE
5300|"          HER husband then away, and she alone,"|FALSE
5300|"          This neighbour came, and in a whining tone,"|FALSE
5300|"          To her observed, when compliments were o'er:--"|FALSE
5300|"          I'm all astonishment, and you deplore,"|FALSE
5300|"          To find that neighbour William's gone from hence,"|FALSE
5300|"          And left your child's completing in suspense,"|FALSE
5300|"          Which now you bear within, and much I fear,"|FALSE
5300|"          That when 'tis born you'll find it wants an ear."|FALSE
5300|"          Your looks sufficiently the fact proclaim,"|FALSE
5300|"          For many instances I've known the same."|FALSE
5300|"          Good heav'ns! replied the lady in a fright;"|FALSE
5300|"          What say you, pray?--the infant won't be right!"|FALSE
5300|"          Shall I be mother to a one-eared child?"|FALSE
5300|"          And know you no relief that's certain styled?"|FALSE
5300|"          Oh yes, there is, rejoined the crafty knave,"|FALSE
5300|"          From such mishap I can the baby save;"|FALSE
5300|"          Yet solemnly I vow, for none but you"|FALSE
5300|"          I'd undertake the toilsome job to do."|FALSE
5300|"          The ills of others, if I may be plain,"|FALSE
5300|"          Except your husband's, never give me pain;"|FALSE
5300|"          But him I'd serve for ever, while I've breath;"|FALSE
5300|"          To do him good I'd e'en encounter death."|FALSE
5300|"          Now let us see, without more talk or fears,"|FALSE
5300|"          If I know how to forge the bantling ears."|FALSE
5300|"          Remember, cried the wife, to make them like."|FALSE
5300|"          Leave that to me, said he, I'll justly strike."|FALSE
5300|"          Then he prepared for work; the dame gave way;"|FALSE
5300|"          Not difficult she proved:--well pleased she lay;"|FALSE
5300|"          Philosophy was never less required,"|FALSE
5300|"          And Andrew's process much the fair admired,"|FALSE
5300|"          Who, to his work extreme attention paid;"|FALSE
5300|"          'Twas now a tendon; then a fold he made,"|FALSE
5300|"          Or cartilage, of which he formed enough,"|FALSE
5300|"          And all without complaining of the stuff."|FALSE
5300|"          To-morrow we will polish it, said he:"|FALSE
5300|"          Then in perfection soon the whole will be;"|FALSE
5300|"          And from repeating this so oft, you'll get"|FALSE
5300|"          As perfect issue as was ever met."|FALSE
5300|"          I'm much obliged to you, the wife replied,"|FALSE
5300|"          A friend is good in whom we may confide."|FALSE
5300|"          NEXT day, when tardy Time had marked the hour;"|FALSE
5300|"          That Andrew hoped again to use his pow'r,"|FALSE
5300|"          He was not plunged in sleep, but briskly flew,"|FALSE
5300|"          His purpose with the charmer to pursue."|FALSE
5300|"          Said he, all other things aside I've laid,"|FALSE
5300|"          This ear to finish, and to lend you aid."|FALSE
5300|"          And I, the dame replied, was on the eve,"|FALSE
5300|"          To send and beg you not the job to leave;"|FALSE
5300|"          Above stairs let us go:--away they ran,"|FALSE
5300|"          And quickly recommenced as they began."|FALSE
5300|"          The work so oft was smoothed, that Alice showed"|FALSE
5300|"          Some scruples lest the ear he had bestowed"|FALSE
5300|"          Should do too much, and to the wily wight,"|FALSE
5300|"          She said, so little you the labour slight,"|FALSE
5300|"          'Twere well if ears no more than two appear;"|FALSE
5300|"          Of that, rejoined the other, never fear;"|FALSE
5300|"          I've guarded thoroughly against defects,"|FALSE
5300|"          Mistake like that shall ne'er your senses vex."|FALSE
5300|"          THE ear howe'er was still in hand the same,"|FALSE
5300|"          When from his journey home the husband came."|FALSE
5300|"          Saluted Alice, who with anxious look,"|FALSE
5300|"          Exclaimed,--your work how finely you forsook,"|FALSE
5300|"          And, but for neighbour Andrew's kindness here,"|FALSE
5300|"          Our child would incomplete have been--an ear,"|FALSE
5300|"          I could not let a thing remain like this,"|FALSE
5300|"          And Andrew would not be to friends remiss,"|FALSE
5300|"          But, worthy man, he left his thriving trade,"|FALSE
5300|"          And for the babe a proper ear has made."|FALSE
5300|"          THE husband, not conceiving how his wife,"|FALSE
5300|"          Could be so weak and ignorant of life,"|FALSE
5300|"          The circumstances made her fully tell,"|FALSE
5300|"          Repeat them o'er and on each action dwell."|FALSE
5300|"          Enraged at length, a pistol by the bed"|FALSE
5300|"          He seized and swore at once he'd shoot her dead."|FALSE
5300|"          The belle with tears replied, howe'er she'd swerved,"|FALSE
5300|"          Such cruel treatment never she deserved."|FALSE
5300|"          Her innocence, and simple, gentle way,"|FALSE
5300|"          At length appeared his frantick rage to lay."|FALSE
5300|"          What injury, continued she, is done?"|FALSE
5300|"          The strictest scrutiny I would not shun;"|FALSE
5300|"          Your goods and money, ev'ry thing is right;"|FALSE
5300|"          And Andrew told me, nothing he would slight;"|FALSE
5300|"          That you would find much more than you could want;"|FALSE
5300|"          And this I hope to me you'll freely grant;"|FALSE
5300|"          If falsehood I advance, my life I'll lose;"|FALSE
5300|"          Your equity, I trust, will me excuse."|FALSE
5300|"          A LITTLE cooled, then William thus replied,"|FALSE
5300|"          We'll say no more; you have been drawn aside;"|FALSE
5300|"          What passed you fancied acting for the best,"|FALSE
5300|"          And I'll consent to put the thing at rest;"|FALSE
5300|"          To nothing good such altercations tend;"|FALSE
5300|"          I've but a word: to that attention lend;"|FALSE
5300|"          Contrive to-morrow that I here entrap"|FALSE
5300|"          This fellow who has caused your sad mishap;"|FALSE
5300|"          You'll utter not a word of what I've said;"|FALSE
5300|"          Be secret or at once I'll strike you dead."|FALSE
5300|"          Adroitly you must act: for instance say;"|FALSE
5300|"          I'm on a second journey gone away;"|FALSE
5300|"          A message or a letter to him send,"|FALSE
5300|"          Soliciting that he'll on you attend,"|FALSE
5300|"          That something you have got to let him know;--"|FALSE
5300|"          To come, no doubt, the rascal won't be slow;"|FALSE
5300|"          Amuse him then with converse most absurd,"|FALSE
5300|"          But of the EAR remember,--not a word;"|FALSE
5300|"          That's finished now, and nothing can require;"|FALSE
5300|"          You'll carefully perform what I desire."|FALSE
5300|"          Poor innocent! the point she nicely hit;"|FALSE
5300|"          Fear oft gives simpletons a sort of wit."|FALSE
5300|"          THE arch gallant arrived; the husband came"|FALSE
