5300|"            \"Must always look another way,"|FALSE
5300|"            \"And if we meet I dare not stay,"|FALSE
5300|"            \"Must ev'ry inclination smother."|FALSE
5300|"            \"I can't believe your love is true;"|FALSE
5300|"            \"I'll never own you really kind"|FALSE
5300|"            \"Unless some certain means you find"|FALSE
5300|"            \"For us to meet without your mother.\""|FALSE
5300|"          Kate answered: \"Were it not too plain"|FALSE
5300|"            \"How warm my love, another strain"|FALSE
5300|"            \"I would employ.  In converse vain"|FALSE
5300|"            \"Let us not waste our moments few;"|FALSE
5300|"            \"But think what it were best to do.\""|FALSE
5300|"            \"If you will please me,\" Robert said,"|FALSE
5300|"            \"You must contrive to change your bed,"|FALSE
5300|"            \"And have it placed--well, let me see--"|FALSE
5300|"            \"Moved to the outer gallery,"|FALSE
5300|"            \"Where you will be alone and free."|FALSE
5300|"            \"We there can meet and chat at leisure"|FALSE
5300|"            \"While others sleep, nor need we fear,"|FALSE
5300|"            \"Of merry tales I have a treasure"|FALSE
5300|"            \"To tell, but cannot tell them here.\""|FALSE
5300|"          Kate smiled at this for she knew well"|FALSE
5300|"          What sort of tales he had to tell;"|FALSE
5300|"          But promised she would do her best"|FALSE
5300|"          And soon accomplish his request."|FALSE
5300|"          It was not easy, you'll admit,"|FALSE
5300|"          But love lends foolish maidens wit;"|FALSE
5300|"          And this is how she managed it."|FALSE
5300|"          The whole night long she kept awake,"|FALSE
5300|"            Snored, sighed and kicked, as one possessed,"|FALSE
5300|"            That parents both could get not rest,"|FALSE
5300|"          So much she made the settle shake."|FALSE
5300|"          This is not strange.  A longing girl,"|FALSE
5300|"            With thoughts of sweetheart in her head,"|FALSE
5300|"          In bed all night will sleepless twirl."|FALSE
5300|"            A flea is in her ear, 'tis said."|FALSE
5300|"          The morning broke.  Of fleas and heat"|FALSE
5300|"          Kitty complained.  \"Let me entreat,"|FALSE
5300|"            \"O mother, I may put my bed"|FALSE
5300|"            \"Out in the gallery,\" she said,"|FALSE
5300|"            \"'Tis cooler there, and Philomel"|FALSE
5300|"            \"Who warbles in the neigh'bring dell"|FALSE
5300|"            \"Will solace me.\" Ready consent"|FALSE
5300|"          The simple mother gave, and went"|FALSE
5300|"          To seek her spouse. \"Our Kate, my dear,"|FALSE
5300|"            \"Will change her bed that she may hear"|FALSE
5300|"            \"The nightingale, and sleep more cool.\""|FALSE
5300|"            \"Wife,\" said the good man, \"You're a fool,"|FALSE
5300|"            \"And Kate too with her nightingale;"|FALSE
5300|"            \"Don't tell me such a foolish tale."|FALSE
5300|"            \"She must remain.  No doubt to-night"|FALSE
5300|"            \"Will fresher be.  I sleep all right"|FALSE
5300|"            \"In spite of heat, and so can she."|FALSE
5300|"            \"Is she more delicate than me?\""|FALSE
5300|"          Incensed was Kate by this denial"|FALSE
5300|"          After so promising a trial,"|FALSE
5300|"          Nor would be beat, but firmly swore"|FALSE
5300|"          To give more trouble than before."|FALSE
5300|"          That night again no wink she slept"|FALSE
5300|"          But groaned and fretted, sighed and wept,"|FALSE
5300|"          Upon her couch so tossed and turned,"|FALSE
5300|"          The anxious mother quite concerned"|FALSE
5300|"          Again her husband sought.  \"Our Kate"|FALSE
5300|"            \"To me seems greatly changed of late."|FALSE
5300|"            \"You are unkind,\" she said to him,"|FALSE
5300|"            \"To thwart her simple, girlish whim."|FALSE
5300|"            \"Why may she not her bed exchange,"|FALSE
5300|"            \"In naught will it the house derange?"|FALSE
5300|"            \"Placed in the passage she's as near"|FALSE
5300|"            \"To us as were she lying here."|FALSE
5300|"            \"You do not love your child, and will"|FALSE
5300|"            \"With your unkindness make her ill.\""|FALSE
5300|"            \"Pray cease,\" the husband cried, \"to scold"|FALSE
5300|"            \"And take your whim.  I ne'er could hold"|FALSE
5300|"            \"My own against a screaming wife;"|FALSE
5300|"            \"You'll drive me mad, upon my life."|FALSE
5300|"            \"Her belly-full our Kate may get"|FALSE
5300|"            \"Of nightingale or of linnet.\""|FALSE
5300|"          The thing was settled.  Kate obeyed,"|FALSE
5300|"          And in a trice her bed was made,"|FALSE
5300|"          And lover signalled.  Who shall say"|FALSE
5300|"          How long to both appeared that day,"|FALSE
5300|"          That tedious day!  But night arrived"|FALSE
5300|"          And Richard too; he had contrived"|FALSE
5300|"          By ladder, and a servant's aid,"|FALSE
5300|"          To reach the chamber of the maid."|FALSE
5300|"          To tell how often they embraced,"|FALSE
5300|"            How changed in form their tenderness,"|FALSE
5300|"          Would lead to nothing but a waste"|FALSE
5300|"            Of time, my readers will confess."|FALSE
5300|"          The longest, most abstruse discourse"|FALSE
5300|"          Would lack precision, want the force"|FALSE
5300|"          Their youthful ardour to portray."|FALSE
5300|"          To understand there's but one way--"|FALSE
5300|"          Experience.  The nightingale"|FALSE
5300|"          Sang all night long his pleasing tale,"|FALSE
5300|"          And though he made but little noise,"|FALSE
5300|"          The lass was satisfied.  Her joys"|FALSE
5300|"          So exquisite that she averred"|FALSE
5300|"          The other nightingale, the bird"|FALSE
5300|"          Who warbles to the woods his bliss,"|FALSE
5300|"          Was but an ass compared with this."|FALSE
5300|"          But nature could not long maintain"|FALSE
5300|"          Of efforts such as these the strain;"|FALSE
5300|"          Their forces spent, the lovers twain"|FALSE
5300|"          In fond embrace fell fast asleep"|FALSE
5300|"          Just as the dawn began to peep:"|FALSE
5300|"          The father as he left his bed"|FALSE
5300|"          By curiosity was led"|FALSE
5300|"          To learn if Kitty soundly slept,"|FALSE
5300|"          And softly to the passage crept."|FALSE
5300|"            \"I'll see the influence,\" he said,"|FALSE
5300|"            \"Of nightingale and change of bed.\""|FALSE
5300|"          With bated breath, upon tip toes,"|FALSE
5300|"          Close to the couch he cautious goes"|FALSE
5300|"          Where Kitty lay in calm repose."|FALSE
5300|"          Excessive heat had made all clothes"|FALSE
5300|"          Unbearable.  The sleeping pair"|FALSE
5300|"          Had cast them off, and lay as bare"|FALSE
5300|"          As our first happy parents were"|FALSE
5300|"          In Paradise.  But in the place"|FALSE
5300|"            Of apple, in her willing hand"|FALSE
5300|"            Kate firmly grasp the magic wand"|FALSE
5300|"          Which served to found the human race,"|FALSE
5300|"          The which to name were a disgrace,"|FALSE
5300|"          Though dames the most refined employ it;"|FALSE
5300|"          Desire it, and much enjoy it,"|FALSE
5300|"          If good Catullus tells us true."|FALSE
5300|"          The father scarce believed his view,"|FALSE
5300|"          But keeping in his bosom pent"|FALSE
5300|"          His anger, to his wife he went,"|FALSE
5300|"          And said, \"Get up, and come with me."|FALSE
5300|"            \"At present I can plainly see"|FALSE
5300|"            \"Why Kate had such anxiety"|FALSE
5300|"            \"To hear the nightingale, for she"|FALSE
5300|"            \"To catch the bird so well has planned"|FALSE
5300|"            \"That now she holds him in her hand.\""|FALSE
5300|"          The mother almost wept for glee."|FALSE
5300|"            \"A nightingale, oh! let me see."|FALSE
5300|"            \"How large is he, and can he sing,"|FALSE
5300|"            \"And will he breed, the pretty thing?"|FALSE
5300|"            \"How did she catch him, clever child?\""|FALSE
5300|"          Despite his grief the good man smiled."|FALSE
5300|"            \"Much more than you expect you'll see."|FALSE
5300|"            \"But hold your tongue, and come with me;"|FALSE
5300|"            \"For if your chattering is heard,"|FALSE
5300|"            \"Away will fly the timid bird;"|FALSE
5300|"            \"And you will spoil our daughter's game.\""|FALSE
5300|"          Who was surprised?  It was the dame."|FALSE
5300|"          Her anger burst into a flame"|FALSE
5300|"          As she the nightingale espied"|FALSE
5300|"          Which Kitty held; she could have cried,"|FALSE
5300|"          And scolded, called her nasty slut,"|FALSE
5300|"          And brazen hussey, bitch, and--but"|FALSE
5300|"          Her husband stopped her. \"What's the use"|FALSE
5300|"            \"Of all your scolding and abuse?"|FALSE
5300|"            \"The mischief's done, in vain may you"|FALSE
5300|"            \"From now till doomsday fret and stew,"|FALSE
5300|"            \"Misfortune done you can't undo,"|FALSE
5300|"            \"But something may be done to mend:"|FALSE
5300|"            \"For notary this instant send,"|FALSE
5300|"            \"Bid holy priest and mayor attend."|FALSE
5300|"            \"For their good offices I wait"|FALSE
5300|"            \"To set this nasty matter straight.\""|FALSE
5300|"          As he discoursed, Richard awoke,"|FALSE
5300|"          And seeing that the sun had broke,"|FALSE
5300|"          These troubled words to Kitty spoke"|FALSE
5300|"            \"Alas, my love, 'tis broad day light,"|FALSE
5300|"            \"How can I now effect my flight?\""|FALSE
5300|"            \"All will go well,\" rejoined the sire,"|FALSE
5300|"            \"I will not grumble, my just ire"|FALSE
5300|"            \"Were useless here; you have committed"|FALSE
5300|"            \"A wrong of which to be acquitted,"|FALSE
5300|"            \"Richard, there is one only way,"|FALSE
5300|"            \"My child you wed without delay."|FALSE
5300|"            \"She's well brought up, young, full of health"|FALSE
5300|"            \"If fortune has not granted wealth,"|FALSE
5300|"            \"Her beauty you do not deny,"|FALSE
5300|"            \"So wed her, or prepare to die.\""|FALSE
5300|"          To hesitate in such a case"|FALSE
5300|"          Would surely have been out of place"|FALSE
5300|"          The girl he loved to take to wife,"|FALSE
5300|"          Or in his prime to lose his life,"|FALSE
5300|"          The point in truth needs no debate,"|FALSE
5300|"          Nor did our Richard hesitate."|FALSE
5300|"          Besides, the most supreme delight"|FALSE
5300|"          Of life he'd tasted one short night,"|FALSE
5300|"          But one, in lovely Kitty's arms;"|FALSE
5300|"          Could he so soon resign her charms!"|FALSE
5300|"          While Richard, pleased with his escape"|FALSE
5300|"          From what he feared an awkward scrape,"|FALSE
5300|"          Was dreaming of his happy choice,"|FALSE
5300|"          Our Kitty, by her father's voice"|FALSE
5300|"          Awakened, from her hand let go"|FALSE
5300|"          The cause of all her joy and woe,"|FALSE
5300|"          And round her naked beauties wound"|FALSE
5300|"          The sheet picked up from off the ground:"|FALSE
5300|"          Meanwhile the notary appears"|FALSE
5300|"          To put an end to all their fears."|FALSE
5300|"          They wrote, they signed, the sealed--and thus"|FALSE
5300|"          The wedding ended free from fuss."|FALSE
5300|"          They left the happy couple there."|FALSE
5300|"          His satisfaction to declare,"|FALSE
5300|"          Thus spoke their father to the pair:"|FALSE
5300|"            \"Take courage, children, have no care;"|FALSE
5300|"            \"The nightingale in cage is pent,"|FALSE
5300|"            \"May sing now to his heart's content.\""|FALSE
5300|"                 EPITAPH OF LA FONTAINE"|FALSE
5300|"                    MADE BY HIMSELF"|FALSE
5300|"          JOHN, as he came, so went away,"|FALSE
5300|"            Consuming capital and pay,"|FALSE
5300|"            Holding superfluous riches cheap;"|FALSE
5300|"          The trick of spending time he knew,"|FALSE
5300|"          Dividing it in portions two,"|FALSE
5300|"            For idling one, and one for sleep."|FALSE
5300|"          THE END."|FALSE
